target: Then , if they die unprovided , no more is the king guilty of their damnation than he was before guilty of those impieties for the which they are now visited .

input: Every subject's duty is the king's duty, but every subject's soul is his own.
target: Every subject's duty is the king's , but every subject's soul is his own .

input: Every sick man in his bed should wash his mote out of his conscience, as should every soldier in the wars.
target: Therefore should every soldier in the wars do as every sick man in his bed : wash every mote out of his conscience .

input: The time was lost because of the preparation that was gained, but it was worth it.
target: And , dying so , death is to him advantage ; or not dying , the time was blessedly lost wherein such preparation was gained .

input: It is certain that every man dies ill, the ill upon his own head.
target: Tis certain , every man that dies ill , the ill upon his own head .

input: The king is not going to answer it.
target: The king is not to answer it .

input: I don't want him to answer for me, and yet I want to fight for him.
target: I do not desire he should answer for me , and yet I determine to fight lustily for him .

input: I heard the king say that he wouldn't be taken advantage of.
target: I myself heard the king say he would not be ransomed .

input: If I live to see it, I will never trust his word again.
target: If I live to see it , I will never trust his word after .

input: You pay him after that.
target: You pay him then .

input: That is a dangerous shot out of an elder gun, that a poor and private displeasure can do against a monarch.
target: That's a perilous shot out of an elder gun , that a poor and private displeasure can do against a monarch .

input: You should go about to turn the sun to ice with a fan in his face and a peacock's feather.
target: You may as well go about to turn the sun to ice with fanning in his face with a peacock's feather .

input: "You'll never trust his word after," is a foolish saying.
target: You'll "never trust his word after." Come , 'tis a foolish saying .

input: Your reproof is not round.
target: Your reproof is something too round .

input: If the time were convenient, I should be angry with you.
target: I should be angry with you if the time were convenient .

input: If you are alive, let it be a fight between us.
target: Let it be a quarrel between us , if you live .

input: I embrace it, I do.
target: I embrace it .

input: I don't know how to know the same thing again.
target: How shall I know thee again ?

input: I will wear it in my bonnet if I get any gage of him.
target: Give me any gage of thine , and I will wear it in my bonnet .

input: I will make it my quarrel if ever I hear it acknowledged.
target: Then , if ever thou dar'st acknowledge it , I will make it my quarrel .

input: There is something there.
target: There .

input: I will wear this in my cap as well.
target: This will I also wear in my cap .

input: I will take a box on the ear if you come to me and say, "This is my glove" after tomorrow.
target: If ever thou come to me and say , after tomorrow , "This is my glove , " by this hand I will take thee a box on the ear .

input: I will challenge it if I ever get the chance to see it.
target: If ever I live to see it , I will challenge it .

input: As well as be hanged, Thou dar'st as well.
target: Thou dar'st as well be hanged .

input: I will do it, even though I am in the king's company.
target: Well , I will do it , though I take thee in the king's company .

input: Don't let your word go to waste.
target: Keep thy word .

input: Well done, Fare thee well.
target: Fare thee well .

input: The French may lay twenty French crowns to one of us, for they will beat us.
target: Indeed , the French may lay twenty French crowns to one they will beat us , for they bear them on their shoulders .

input: The king himself will be a clipper tomorrow, and it is not English treason to cut French crowns.
target: But it is no English treason to cut French crowns , and tomorrow the king himself will be a clipper .

input: What your reverence will bring us to.
target: Of what your reverence shall incite us to .

input: How you impawn our person, how you awake our sleeping sword of war, take heed.
target: Therefore take heed how you impawn our person , How you awake our sleeping sword of war .

input: Under this conjuration, speak, my lord, for we will hear, note, and believe in heart, that what you speak is in your conscience washed as pure as sin with the crucifixion.
target: Under this conjuration , speak , my lord , For we will hear , note , and believe in heart That what you speak is in your conscience washed As pure as sin with baptism .

input: You peers owe yourselves, your lives, and services to this imperial throne, then hear me.
target: Then hear me , gracious sovereign , and you peers That owe yourselves , your lives , and services To this imperial throne .

input: It is upon the king!
target: Upon the king !

input: Let our lives, our souls, our debts, our wives, our children, and our sins be forgiven by the king.
target: Let us our lives , our souls , our debts , our careful wives , our children , and our sins lay on the king !

input: We have to bear it all.
target: We must bear all .

input: Twin-born with greatness, subject to the breath of every fool, whose sense no longer can feel, but his own wringing.
target: O hard condition , Twin-born with greatness , subject to the breath Of every fool , whose sense no more can feel But his own wringing .

input: Is it possible to neglect kings that private men enjoy.
target: What infinite heart's ease Must kings neglect that private men enjoy ?

input: Save ceremony, save general ceremony, what are the kings that privates do not have?
target: And what have kings that privates have not too , Save ceremony , save general ceremony ?

input: What art do you think about the idol ceremony?
target: And what art thou , thou idol ceremony ?

input: What kind of god art do you think suffers more mortal griefs than worshippers?
target: What kind of god art thou , that suffer'st more Of mortal griefs than do thy worshippers ?

input: What are the things that are going to happen?
target: What are thy comings in ?

input: Show me but my worth, O ceremony.
target: O ceremony , show me but thy worth !

input: What is it about her that makes her love her?
target: What is thy soul of adoration ?

input: Creating awe and fear in other men is where the art is less happy than they are.
target: Art thou aught else but place , degree , and form , Creating awe and fear in other men , Wherein thou art less happy , being feared , Than they in fearing ?

input: But poisoned flattery, instead of homage sweet, what drink'st Thou oft?
target: What drink'st thou oft , instead of homage sweet , But poisoned flattery ?

input: Be sick, great greatness, and bid your ceremony give the cure.
target: Oh , be sick , great greatness , And bid thy ceremony give thee cure !

input: Think about it, with titles blown from adulation, the fiery fever will go out.
target: Think'st thou the fiery fever will go out With titles blown from adulation ?

input: Is it possible that it will give place to flexure and low bending?
target: Will it give place to flexure and low bending ?

input: Can you tell me when to command the health of the beggar's knee.
target: Canst thou , when thou command'st the beggar's knee , Command the health of it ?

input: That play'st so subtly with a king's repose, is a proud dream.
target: No , thou proud dream , That play'st so subtly with a king's repose .

input: For ceremony, such a wretch, Winding up days with toil and nights with sleep, and had the forehand and vantage of a king.
target: And , but for ceremony , such a wretch , Winding up days with toil and nights with sleep , Had the forehand and vantage of a king .

input: My lord, your nobles are jealous of your absence, so seek through your camp to find you.
target: My lord , your nobles , jealous of your absence , Seek through your camp to find you .

input: Good old knight, collect them all together at my tent.
target: Good old knight , Collect them all together at my tent .

input: I'll be there before thee.
target: I'll be before thee .

input: I will do that, my lord.
target: I shall do't , my lord .

input: My soldiers are steeled by the God of battles.
target: O God of battles , steel my soldiers ' hearts .

input: They should be possessed not with fear.
target: Possess them not with fear .

input: Take from them now, the sense of reck'ning ere th'opposed numbers, Pluck their hearts from them.
target: Take from them now The sense of reck'ning ere th ' opposed numbers Pluck their hearts from them .

input: Don't think about the fault my father made in compassing the crown, not today.
target: Not today , O Lord , Oh , not today , think not upon the fault My father made in compassing the crown .

input: I Richard's body have been laid to rest again, and on it have given more contrite tears, than from it issued forced drops of blood.
target: I Richard's body have interred anew , And on it have bestowed more contrite tears Than from it issued forced drops of blood .

input: Five hundred poor are in yearly pay, who twice a day their withered hands hold up Toward heaven to pardon their blood.
target: Five hundred poor I have in yearly pay , Who twice a day their withered hands hold up Toward heaven to pardon blood .

input: The sad and solemn priests sing for Richard's soul in one of the two chantries I have built.
target: And I have built Two chantries where the sad and solemn priests Sing still for Richard's soul .

input: I will do more since I know that my penitence comes after all, and that I need a pardon.
target: More will I do , Though all that I can do is nothing worth , Since that my penitence comes after all , Imploring pardon .

input: My liege is here.
target: My liege .

input: I know my brother's errand, my brother Gloucester's voice.
target: My brother Gloucester's voice. , Ay , I know thy errand .

input: I will travel with thee.
target: I will go with thee .

input: Everything stays for me on the day, my friends and me.
target: The day , my friends , and all things stay for me .

input: Our armor was gild by the sun.
target: The sun doth gild our armor .

input: My lords are up.
target: Up , my lords .

input: Now, my Lord, what are you doing?
target: Now , my Lord Constable ?

input: How are our steeds for the present service?
target: Hark how our steeds for present service neigh .

input: I think it's a good thing!
target: Ha !

input: Is it possible that you will have them weep our horses' blood?
target: What , will you have them weep our horses ' blood ?

input: How will we see their natural tears?
target: How shall we then behold their natural tears ?

input: You French peers, the English are facing a lot of questions.
target: The English are embattled , you French peers .

input: To the horse, you princes, straight to the horse.
target: To horse , you gallant princes , straight to horse .

input: What should we say?
target: What's to say ?

input: Let the trumpets sound The tucket sonance and the note to mount, for our approach shall so much dare the field that England shall couch down in fear and yield.
target: Then let the trumpets sound The tucket sonance and the note to mount , For our approach shall so much dare the field That England shall couch down in fear and yield .

input: My lords of France, why do you stay for so long?
target: Why do you stay so long , my lords of France ?

input: The morning field is favored by the island carrions, who are desperate for their bones.
target: Yond island carrions , desperate of their bones , Ill-favoredly become the morning field .

input: Big Mars seems to be in financial trouble in their host.
target: Big Mars seems bankrupt in their beggared host And faintly through a rusty beaver peeps .

input: They said their prayers and stayed for the death.
target: They have said their prayers , and they stay for death .

input: We should send them dinners and fresh suits, and give their horses provender, after we fight with them.
target: Shall we go send them dinners and fresh suits , And give their fasting horses provender , And after fight with them ?

input: On to the field!
target: On , to the field !

input: I'm going to use the banner from the trumpet for my haste.
target: I will the banner from a trumpet take And use it for my haste .

input: Come, come, come away.
target: Come , come away .

input: The sun is high, and we are out of our clothes.
target: The sun is high , and we outwear the day .

input: What is the location of the king?
target: Where is the king ?

input: The king is on a ride to view their battle.
target: The king himself is rode to view their battle .

input: They have threescore thousand men who are fighting.
target: Of fighting men they have full threescore thousand .

input: There are five to one.
target: There's five to one .

input: All of them are fresh.
target: Besides , they all are fresh .

input: God struck us with his arms.
target: God's arm strike with us !

input: The odds are very fearful.
target: Tis a fearful odds .

input: You and princes all, God be with you.
target: God be wi ' you , princes all .

input: I'll take care of my charge.
target: I'll to my charge .

input: Good luck Salisbury, farewell, and good luck going with thee.
target: Farewell , good Salisbury , and good luck go with thee .

input: Thank you lord, farewell.
target: Farewell , kind lord .

input: Today is a fight to be fought.
target: Fight valiantly today .

input: I don't think the art is framed of the true truth of the matter.
target: And yet I do thee wrong to mind thee of it , For thou art framed of the firm truth of valor .

input: He is full of kindness and also full of bravery.
target: He is as full of valor as of kindness , Princely in both .

input: Ten thousand of those men in England do not work today.
target: Oh , that we now had here But one ten thousand of those men in England That do no work today .

input: What is he that wants to do?
target: What's he that wishes so ?

input: Is my cousin Westmoreland here?
target: My cousin Westmoreland ?

input: No, my fair cousin.
target: No , my fair cousin .

input: If we are marked to die, we are enough to do our country's loss, and the fewer men we have, the greater share of honor.
target: If we are marked to die , we are enough To do our country loss ; and if to live , The fewer men , the greater share of honor .

input: I pray thee don't have to have one man anymore.
target: God's will , I pray thee wish not one man more .

input: I don't care if men wear my clothes because I don't want them to wear my gold.
target: By Jove , I am not covetous for gold Nor care I who doth feed upon my cost ; It yearns me not if men my garments wear ; Such outward things dwell not in my desires .

input: I am the most offending soul alive if it is a sin to honor.
target: But if it be a sin to covet honor , I am the most offending soul alive .

input: I wish a man from England wasn't my friend.
target: No , faith , my coz , wish not a man from England .

input: I would not lose so much honor as one man more would share from me, for the best hope I have.
target: God's peace , I would not lose so great an honor As one man more , methinks , would share from me , For the best hope I have .

input: Do not wish for one more.
target: Oh , do not wish one more !

input: His passport will be made and crowns will be put into his purse.
target: His passport shall be made , And crowns for convoy put into his purse .

input: We wouldn't die in that man's company, that fears his fellowship to die with us.
target: We would not die in that man's company That fears his fellowship to die with us .

input: He will see this day, and live old age, and will say, "Tomorrow is Saint Crispian." Then he will show his scars, and say, "These wounds I had on Crispin's."
target: He that shall see this day , and live old age , Will yearly on the vigil feast his neighbors And say , "Tomorrow is Saint Crispian." Then will he strip his sleeve and show his scars , And say , "These wounds I had on Crispin's day."

input: If our minds are ready, all things are ready.
target: All things are ready if our minds be so .

input: The man's mind is moving in a backward direction.
target: Perish the man whose mind is backward now !

input: Thou do not wish for more help from England.
target: Thou dost not wish more help from England , coz ?

input: God, be with you all.
target: God be with you all .

input: Tucket once more I come to know of thee, King Harry, if for his sake he will now compound.
target: Tucket Once more I come to know of thee , King Harry , If for thy ransom thou wilt now compound , Before thy most assured overthrow .

input: The gulf is so close to the art that Thou needs must be englutted.
target: For certainly thou art so near the gulf Thou needs must be englutted .

input: The constable wants the followers of repentance to make a peaceful and sweet retirement from the fields where they live.
target: Besides , in mercy , The constable desires thee thou wilt mind Thy followers of repentance , that their souls May make a peaceful and a sweet retire From off these fields where , wretches , their poor bodies Must lie and fester .

input: Who has sent thee?
target: Who hath sent thee now ?

input: The person who was the constable of France.
target: The constable of France .

input: I ask thee to bear my previous answer back.
target: I pray thee , bear my former answer back .

input: Sell my bones if you want to achieve me.
target: Bid them achieve me and then sell my bones .

input: The man that used to sell the lion's skin was killed by the animal.
target: The man that once did sell the lion's skin While the beast lived was killed with hunting him .

input: I trust that we will find native graves for many of our bodies, and that we will witness live in brass of this day's work.
target: A many of our bodies shall no doubt Find native graves , upon the which , I trust , Shall witness live in brass of this day's work .

input: The sun will greet those that leave their bones in France, and they will be famed, and they will leave their earthly parts to choke your clime.
target: And those that leave their valiant bones in France , Dying like men though buried in your dunghills , They shall be famed ; for there the sun shall greet them And draw their honors reeking up to heaven , Leaving their earthly parts to choke your clime ,

input: Their writers say that KingPepin, who deposed Childeric, Did, as heir general, was the daughter of King Clothair, who made claim and title to the crown of France.
target: Besides , their writers say , King Pepin , which deposed Childeric , Did , as heir general , being descended Of Blithild , which was daughter to King Clothair , Make claim and title to the crown of France .

input: It was corrupt and naught for Hugh Capet to take the crown of Charles the duke of Lorraine, the sole heir male of the true line and stock of Charles the great.
target: Hugh Capet also , who usurped the crown Of Charles the duke of Lorraine , sole heir male Of the true line and stock of Charles the Great , To find his title with some shows of truth , Though in pure truth it was corrupt and naught , Conveyed himself as th ' heir to th ' Lady Lingare , Daughter to Charlemagne , who was the son To Lewis the Emperor , and Lewis the son Of Charles the Great .

input: King Lewis the Tenth, who was the sole heir to the Capet, wore the crown of France until he was satisfied with Queen Isabel, his grandmother.
target: Also King Lewis the Tenth , Who was sole heir to the usurper Capet , Could not keep quiet in his conscience , Wearing the crown of France , till satisfied That fair Queen Isabel , his grandmother , Was lineal of the Lady Ermengare , Daughter to Charles the foresaid duke of Lorraine , By the which marriage the line of Charles the Great Was reunited to the crown of France .

input: King Lewis' satisfaction, Hugh Capet's claim, and KingPepin's title all appear to be to hold in right and title of the female.
target: So that , as clear as is the summer's sun , King Pepin's title and Hugh Capet's claim , King Lewis his satisfaction , all appear To hold in right and title of the female .

input: We are but warriors for the working day, our gayness and gilt are all besmirched by the rainy marching in the painful field.
target: Let me speak proudly : tell the constable We are but warriors for the working day ; Our gayness and our gilt are all besmirched With rainy marching in the painful field .

input: Good argument, I hope that we will not fly, and time has worn us into slovenry, there's not a piece of feather in our host.
target: There's not a piece of feather in our host , Good argument , I hope , we will not fly , And time hath worn us into slovenry .

input: If they do this, then I will be forced to pay a large amount of money.
target: If they do this , As , if God please , they shall , my ransom then Will soon be levied .

input: Herald, save the labor of the man.
target: Herald , save thou thy labor .

input: Come no more for money, gentle herald.
target: Come thou no more for ransom , gentle herald .

input: I swear, but these my joints, if they have, as I will leave 'em them, Shall yield them little.
target: They shall have none , I swear , but these my joints , Which , if they have , as I will leave 'em them , Shall yield them little .

input: Tell the person who is in charge.
target: Tell the constable .

input: I will be with King Harry.
target: I shall , King Harry .

input: And so do you fare well.
target: And so fare thee well .

input: Thou shalt never hear herald anymore.
target: Thou never shalt hear herald anymore .

input: I am afraid that he will come again for a ransom.
target: I fear thou wilt once more come again for a ransom .

input: I beg The leading of the vaward, most sincerely on my knee.
target: My lord , most humbly on my knee I beg The leading of the vaward .

input: Take it and be brave York.
target: Take it , brave York .

input: Soldiers, march away, and how Thou pleasest, God, dispose the day.
target: Now , soldiers , march away , And how Thou pleasest , God , dispose the day .

input: There is a yield, and there is a curve.
target: Yield , cur .

input: He said his name was Master Fer.
target: He says his name is Master Fer .

input: Master Fer is a master.
target: Master Fer .

input: What are he talking about?
target: What are his words ?

input: He is praying that you will save his life.
target: He prays you to save his life .

input: He is a gentleman of a good house and will give you two hundred crowns in exchange for your freedom.
target: He is a gentleman of a good house , and for his ransom he will give you two hundred crowns .

input: I will take the crowns if you tell him that my fury will abate.
target: Tell him my fury shall abate , and I the crowns will take .

input: I'm Expound unto me, boy.
target: Expound unto me , boy .

input: He gives you a thousand thanks, and he thinks that he is the most brave, valorous, and three times- worthy seigneur of England.
target: He gives you upon his knees a thousand thanks , and he esteems himself happy that he hath fall'n into the hands of one , as he thinks , the most brave , valorous , and thrice- worthy seigneur of England .

input: I will perform a mercy show when I suck blood.
target: As I suck blood , I will some mercy show .

input: I encourage you to follow me.
target: Follow me .

input: I have never heard a voice issue like that before.
target: I did never know so full a voice issue from so empty a heart .

input: I have to stay with the lackeys with the luggage.
target: I must stay with the lackeys with the luggage of our camp .

input: If he knew of it, the French might have a good chance of catching us.
target: The French might have a good prey of us if he knew of it , for there is none to guard it but boys .

input: Shame and reproach are mocked in our feathers.
target: Reproach and everlasting shame Sits mocking in our plumes .

input: Do not try to run away.
target: Do not run away .

input: All our ranks are broke, why?
target: Why , all our ranks are broke .

input: It is perdurable shame.
target: O perdurable shame !

input: We should stab ourselves.
target: Let's stab ourselves .

input: These are the wretches that we played at the dice.
target: Be these the wretches that we played at dice for ?

input: Is this the king that we sent to get his attention?
target: Is this the king we sent to for his ransom ?

input: Nothing but shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame, shame,
target: Shame , and eternal shame , nothing but shame !

input: Let us die, please.
target: Let us die .

input: He that will not follow Bourbon now, let him go, and with his cap in hand, as a base pander hold the chamber door, and as a slave, no gentle than my dog.
target: And he that will not follow Bourbon now , Let him go hence , and with his cap in hand Like a base pander hold the chamber door , Whilst by a slave , no gentler than my dog , His fairest daughter is contaminate .

input: It was disorder that spoiled us, friend us now.
target: Disorder , that hath spoiled us , friend us now .

input: Let us go offer up our lives and make a difference.
target: Let us on heaps go offer up our lives .

input: If any order might be thought upon, we would smother up the English in our throngs.
target: We are enough yet living in the field To smother up the English in our throngs , If any order might be thought upon .

input: The devil has to take order now.
target: The devil take order now !

input: I will go to the throng.
target: I'll to the throng .

input: Let life be short, otherwise shame will be too long.
target: Let life be short , else shame will be too long .

input: The French should keep the field.
target: Yet keep the French the field .

input: The duke of York is a friend of your Majesty.
target: The duke of York commends him to your Majesty .

input: Is he still alive, a good uncle?
target: Lives he , good uncle ?

input: Within this hour, I saw him down, three times up again, and fighting.
target: Thrice within this hour I saw him down , thrice up again and fighting .

input: He was all blood from the helmet to the spur.
target: From helmet to the spur , all blood he was .

input: In which array, brave soldier, doth he lie, and by his bloody side, The noble earl of Suffolk also lies.
target: In which array , brave soldier , doth he lie , Larding the plain , and by his bloody side , Yoke-fellow to his honor-owing wounds , The noble earl of Suffolk also lies .

input: Suffolk first died, and York, all haggled over, came to him, and kissed the gashes, that bloodily did yawn upon his face.
target: Suffolk first died , and York , all haggled over , Comes to him where in gore he lay insteeped And takes him by the beard , kisses the gashes That bloodily did yawn upon his face .

input: "Tarry, my cousin Suffolk," cried my cousin Suffolk.
target: And cries aloud , "Tarry , my cousin Suffolk .

input: My soul will keep company with heaven.
target: My soul shall thine keep company to heaven .

input: I came and cheered him up after he said " Tarry, sweet soul, for mine, then fly abreast, As in this glorious and well-fought-en field We kept together in our chivalry."
target: Tarry , sweet soul , for mine ; then fly abreast , As in this glorious and well-foughten field We kept together in our chivalry." Upon these words I came and cheered him up .

input: The French reinforced their scattered men.
target: The French have reinforced their scattered men .

input: Then every soldier kills his prisoners.
target: Then every soldier kill his prisoners .

input: The word should be given through.
target: Give the word through .

input: The kings of France would hold up the Salic law to prevent your Highness from claiming from the female, rather than hiding them in a net.
target: So do the kings of France unto this day , Howbeit they would hold up this Salic law To bar your Highness claiming from the female And rather choose to hide them in a net Than amply to imbar their crooked titles Usurped from you and your progenitors .

input: Is it possible that I have right and conscience to make this claim?
target: May I with right and conscience make this claim ?

input: The Book of Numbers says "When the man dies, let the inheritance Descend unto the daughter." Gracious lord, stand for your own, look back into your life.
target: The sin upon my head , dread sovereign , For in the Book of Numbers is it writ : "When the man dies , let the inheritance Descend unto the daughter." Gracious lord , Stand for your own , unwind your bloody flag , Look back into your mighty ancestors .

input: Go to your great-grandsire's tomb, from whom you claim, my dread lord.
target: Go , my dread lord , to your great-grandsire's tomb , From whom you claim .

input: Stood smiling to behold his lion's whelp, while Edward the Black Prince played a tragedy on the French ground.
target: Invoke his warlike spirit And your great-uncle's , Edward the Black Prince , Who on the French ground played a tragedy , Making defeat on the full power of France Whiles his most mighty father on a hill Stood smiling to behold his lion's whelp Forage in blood of French nobility .

input: O noble English, that could entertain, with half their forces the full pride of France, and let another half stand laughing, all out of work and cold for action!
target: O noble English , that could entertain With half their forces the full pride of France And let another half stand laughing by , All out of work and cold for action !

input: Awake remembrance of the dead, and with your puissant arm, continue their feats.
