target: A friend should bear his friend's infirmities , But Brutus makes mine greater than they are .

input: You have to practice them on me before I do.
target: I do not , till you practice them on me .

input: You are not in love with me.
target: You love me not .

input: I don't like the way you do things.
target: I do not like your faults .

input: A friendly eye wouldn't be able to see such faults.
target: A friendly eye could never see such faults .

input: A flatterer's would not appear as large as high Olympus.
target: A flatterer's would not , though they do appear As huge as high Olympus .

input: I could feel My spirit in mine eyes.
target: Oh , I could weep My spirit from mine eyes .

input: You should sheathe your dagger.
target: Sheathe your dagger .

input: It will have scope if you are angry when you will.
target: Be angry when you will , it shall have scope .

input: Do what you will and it will be funnier.
target: Do what you will , dishonor shall be humor .

input: I was very angry when I spoke that.
target: When I spoke that , I was ill-tempered too .

input: Is it possible that you confess so much?
target: Do you confess so much ?

input: Give me something to hold on to.
target: Give me your hand .

input: My heart is also included.
target: And my heart too .

input: It is O Brutus!
target: O Brutus !

input: The matter is what?
target: What's the matter ?

input: When my mother gave me a rash humor that made me forget, have you not loved me enough to bear with me?
target: Have not you love enough to bear with me , When that rash humor which my mother gave me Makes me forgetful ?

input: Affirmative, Cassius.
target: Yes , Cassius .

input: From now on, when you are over-earnest with your Brutus, he will think of your mother and leave you.
target: And from henceforth When you are over-earnest with your Brutus , He'll think your mother chides and leave you so .

input: How are you now?
target: How now ?

input: The matter is what?
target: What's the matter ?

input: You generals are for shame.
target: For shame , you generals !

input: What are you talking about?
target: What do you mean ?

input: Love and being friends with two such men should be a priority.
target: Love , and be friends as two such men should be .

input: I'm sure that I have seen more years than you.
target: For I have seen more years , I'm sure , than ye .

input: You should bear with him, Brutus.
target: Bear with him , Brutus .

input: He is his fashion.
target: Tis his fashion .

input: When he knows his time, I will know his humor.
target: I'll know his humor when he knows his time .

input: What should the wars do with these jigging fools?
target: What should the wars do with these jigging fools ?

input: Therefore, a companion.
target: Companion , hence !

input: Be gone, away, away, be gone.
target: Away , away , be gone .

input: Titinius and Lucillius bid the commanders to lodge their companies tonight.
target: Lucillius and Titinius , bid the commanders Prepare to lodge their companies tonight .

input: Messala will be with you immediately to us.
target: And come yourselves , and bring Messala with you , Immediately to us .

input: I didn't think you could have been so angry.
target: I did not think you could have been so angry .

input: I am sick of all the griefs.
target: O Cassius , I am sick of many griefs .

input: There is a dead person in this picture.
target: Portia is dead .

input: Is it possible that Portia is Ha?
target: Ha , Portia ?

input: She is no longer with us.
target: She is dead .

input: It is insupportable and touching to lose.
target: O insupportable and touching loss !

input: What sickness do you experience?
target: Upon what sickness ?

input: Impatient of my absence, and grief that young Octavius with Mark Antony have made themselves so strong, for with her death, they swallowed fire.
target: Impatient of my absence , And grief that young Octavius with Mark Antony Have made themselves so strong , for with her death That tidings came , with this she fell distract And , her attendants absent , swallowed fire .

input: And died so, did you?
target: And died so ?

input: Even so is true.
target: Even so .

input: O ye gods of immortality!
target: O ye immortal gods !

input: My heart is thirsty for that noble pledge.
target: My heart is thirsty for that noble pledge .

input: Wait till the wine o'erswell the cup.
target: Fill , Lucius , till the wine o'erswell the cup .

input: I don't want to drink too much of Brutus.
target: I can not drink too much of Brutus ' love .

input: Call in question our necessities now, because we are close to this taper here.
target: Now sit we close about this taper here And call in question our necessities .

input: Is it possible that art is gone?
target: Portia , art thou gone ?

input: I am praying that you will not be no more.
target: No more , I pray you .

input: Messala, I have received letters from Octavius and Mark Antony, who came down upon us with a mighty power to destroy us.
target: Messala , I have here received letters That young Octavius and Mark Antony Come down upon us with a mighty power , Bending their expedition toward Philippi .

input: The letters of the selfsame tenor are in my possession.
target: Myself have letters of the selfsame tenor .

input: What addition do you have?
target: With what addition ?

input: The proscription of outlawry, Octavius, Antony, and Lepidus have led to the death of hundreds of senators.
target: That by proscription and bills of outlawry , Octavius , Antony , and Lepidus Have put to death an hundred senators .

input: Our letters are not in agreement.
target: Therein our letters do not well agree .

input: Cicero was one of the seventy senators that died by their proscriptions.
target: Mine speak of seventy senators that died By their proscriptions , Cicero being one .

input: Cicero one, what?
target: Cicero one ?

input: Cicero is dead, and by that order of proscription.
target: Cicero is dead , And by that order of proscription .

input: No, Messala.
target: No , Messala .

input: There was nothing in your letters to her.
target: Nor nothing in your letters writ of her ?

input: Messala, there is nothing.
target: Nothing , Messala .

input: It's strange that I think that way.
target: That methinks is strange .

input: Why do you want to ask that?
target: Why ask you ?

input: Did you hear about her in your life?
target: Hear you aught of her in yours ?

input: No, my lord, no.
target: No , my lord .

input: As a Roman, tell me that you are right.
target: Now , as you are a Roman , tell me true .

input: I tell the truth like a Roman does.
target: Then like a Roman bear the truth I tell .

input: She is dead, and in a strange manner.
target: For certain she is dead , and by strange manner .

input: Why, farewell to me, Portia.
target: Why , farewell , Portia .

input: We need to die, Messala.
target: We must die , Messala .

input: I have the patience to endure it now because I have meditated that she must die once.
target: With meditating that she must die once , I have the patience to endure it now .

input: Great losses should endure even so.
target: Even so great men great losses should endure .

input: I have the same amount of this in art as you do, but my nature wouldn't allow it.
target: I have as much of this in art as you , But yet my nature could not bear it so .

input: To our work that is still going strong.
target: Well , to our work alive .

input: What do you think about the march to Philippi right now?
target: What do you think Of marching to Philippi presently ?

input: I don't think it is a good idea.
target: I do not think it good .

input: Are you the one with your reason?
target: Your reason ?

input: It's better that the enemy look for us.
target: This it is : 'T is better that the enemy seek us .

input: He will waste his means, weary his soldiers, and doing himself offense, while we are lying still, and are full of rest.
target: So shall he waste his means , weary his soldiers , Doing himself offense , whilst we , lying still , Are full of rest , defense , and nimbleness .

input: The enemy, marching along by them, will make a full number up, come on refreshed, new-added, and encouraged, From which advantage shall we cut him off.
target: The enemy , marching along by them , By them shall make a fuller number up , Come on refreshed , new-added , and encouraged , From which advantage shall we cut him off If at Philippi we do face him there , These people at our back .

input: Under your pardon, please hear me, good brother.
target: Hear me , good brother , Under your pardon .

input: We have tried the best of our friends, and our cause is ripe, you must note.
target: You must note beside , That we have tried the utmost of our friends , Our legions are brim-full , our cause is ripe .

input: The enemy increase their strength every day.
target: The enemy increaseth every day .

input: At the height, we are ready to decline.
target: We , at the height , are ready to decline .

input: We have to take the current when it serves or lose our ventures when we are afloat.
target: On such a full sea are we now afloat , And we must take the current when it serves Or lose our ventures .

input: Continue, with your will.
target: Then , with your will , go on .

input: We'll meet them at Philippi, along with ourselves.
target: We'll along ourselves , and meet them at Philippi .

input: The deep of night is crept upon our talk, and nature must obey necessity, which we will niggard with a little rest.
target: The deep of night is crept upon our talk , And nature must obey necessity , Which we will niggard with a little rest .

input: There isn't anything left to say.
target: There is no more to say ?

input: There is no more.
target: No more .

input: Thank you for a good night.
target: Good night .

input: We will rise and so will you tomorrow.
target: Early tomorrow will we rise and hence .

input: It's Lucius!
target: Lucius !

input: Don't come such division 'tween our souls.'
target: Never come such division 'tween our souls .

input: Let it not be, Brutus.
target: Let it not , Brutus .

input: Is now become a god and must bend his body if Caesar does not nod on him.
target: Is now become a god , and Cassius is A wretched creature and must bend his body If Caesar carelessly but nod on him .

input: He had a fit when he was in Spain and I did a mark on how he did shake.
target: He had a fever when he was in Spain , And when the fit was on him , I did mark How he did shake .

input: This god did shake, it was true.
target: Tis true , this god did shake !

input: The same eye whose bend doth awe the world lost his luster as his lips did from their color.
target: His coward lips did from their color fly , And that same eye whose bend doth awe the world Did lose his luster .

input: I heard him groan and that tongue of his that bade the Romans, so I told him to write his speeches in their books, as a sick girl.
target: I did hear him groan , Ay , and that tongue of his that bade the Romans Mark him and write his speeches in their books , "Alas , " it cried , "give me some drink , Titinius , " As a sick girl .

input: The man of such a feeble temper should get the start of the majestic world and bear the palm alone.
target: Ye gods , it doth amaze me A man of such a feeble temper should So get the start of the majestic world And bear the palm alone .

input: Another general shout.
target: Another general shout !

input: I believe that the applauses are for some new honors that are heaped on Caesar.
target: I do believe that these applauses are For some new honors that are heaped on Caesar .

input: He doth bestride the narrow world, and we have to walk under his huge legs to find our own graves.
target: Why , man , he doth bestride the narrow world Like a Colossus , and we petty men Walk under his huge legs and peep about To find ourselves dishonorable graves .

input: At some point, men are masters of their fate.
target: Men at some time are masters of their fates .

input: The fault is not in the stars, but in ourselves.
target: The fault , dear Brutus , is not in our stars But in ourselves , that we are underlings .

input: What should be in that "Caesar?"
target: Brutus and Caesar , what should be in that "Caesar" ?

input: Why do you think that name should be sounded more than yours?
target: Why should that name be sounded more than yours ?

input: Yours is as fair a name as you can write them together.
target: Write them together , yours is as fair a name .

input: Sound them and they will become the mouth as well.
target: Sound them , it doth become the mouth as well .

input: Everything is going well.
target: Everything is well .

input: I wish you a good night.
target: Good night , my lord .

input: Good brother, good night.
target: Good night , good brother .

input: Good night, Lord Brutus.
target: Good night , Lord Brutus .

input: Thank you everyone for farewell.
target: Farewell , everyone .

input: Give me the gown, I need it.
target: Give me the gown .

input: What is the location of the instrument?
target: Where is thy instrument ?

input: In the tent is where I am.
target: Here in the tent .

input: What is it that he speaks thest drowsily?
target: What , thou speak'st drowsily ?

input: Call some of my friends.
target: Call Claudio and some other of my men .

input: I will have them sleep on the cushions in my tent.
target: I'll have them sleep on cushions in my tent .

input: Varrus and Claudio were together.
target: Varrus and Claudio !

input: Is it my lord who calls?
target: Calls my lord ?

input: I am praying that you lie in my tent and sleep.
target: I pray you , sirs , lie in my tent and sleep .

input: It is possible that I will raise you by and on behalf of my brother Cassius.
target: It may be I shall raise you by and by On business to my brother Cassius .

input: We will be standing and watching your pleasure.
target: So please you , we will stand and watch your pleasure .

input: Here's the book that I sought for.
target: Look , Lucius , here's the book I sought for so .

input: I put it in the pocket of my dress.
target: I put it in the pocket of my gown .

input: I was pretty sure that your lordship did not give me it.
target: I was sure your lordship did not give it me .

input: Is it possible for you to hold up your heavy eyes for a while and touch your instrument?
target: Canst thou hold up thy heavy eyes awhile , And touch thy instrument a strain or two ?

input: My lord, an 't please you'.
target: Ay , my lord , an 't please you .

input: My boy says it does.
target: It does , my boy .

input: I trouble thee too much, but I am willing to work with you.
target: I trouble thee too much , but thou art willing .

input: It is my responsibility, sir.
target: It is my duty , sir .

input: I don't want you to urge your duty past your might.
target: I should not urge thy duty past thy might .

input: Young bloods look for a time of rest.
target: I know young bloods look for a time of rest .

input: My lord, I have already slept.
target: I have slept , my lord , already .

input: It was well done, and you should sleep again.
target: It was well done , and thou shalt sleep again .

input: I won't hold thee for very long.
target: I will not hold thee long .

input: I will be a good person if I do live.
target: If I do live , I will be good to thee .

input: This is a song that is sleepy.
target: This is a sleepy tune .

input: Good night, Layst your leaden pepper upon my boy, that plays the music.
target: O murderous slumber , Layst thou thy leaden mace upon my boy That plays thee music ? , Gentle knave , good night .

input: I won't do so much wrong to wake thee up.
target: I will not do thee so much wrong to wake thee .

input: Good night, and good boy.
target: And , good boy , good night .

input: Let me see, let me see.
target: Let me see , let me see .

input: Where I left reading is not the leaf turned down.
target: Is not the leaf turned down Where I left reading ?

input: I think that it is here.
target: Here it is , I think .

input: I think it's the weakness of my eyes that shapes this monster.
target: I think it is the weakness of mine eyes That shapes this monstrous apparition .

input: Art, what comes upon me?
target: It comes upon me. , Art thou any thing ?

input: That makes my blood cold and my hair to look at, that is art.
target: Art thou some god , some angel , or some devil That makest my blood cold and my hair to stare ?

input: Speak to me what you think about it.
target: Speak to me what thou art .

input: The evil spirit was called Brutus.
target: Thy evil spirit , Brutus .

input: Why does it happen to you?
target: Why comest thou ?

input: To let thee know that I am at Philippi.
target: To tell thee thou shalt see me at Philippi .

input: Well, then I will see thee again.
target: Well , then I shall see thee again ?

input: There is Ay at Philippi.
target: Ay , at Philippi .

input: I will see thee at Philippi, then.
target: Why , I will see thee at Philippi , then .

input: I would hold more talks with thee.
target: Ill spirit , I would hold more talk with thee .

input: The man is named Claudio.
target: Claudio !

input: My lord, the strings are not true.
target: The strings , my lord , are false .

input: He thinks he is still playing the instrument.
target: He thinks he still is at his instrument .

input: The man is awake.
target: Lucius , awake .

input: My lord, what are you saying?
target: My lord ?

input: Did you dream that you cried out?
target: Didst thou dream , Lucius , that thou so criedst out ?

input: I am not aware that I cried.
target: My lord , I do not know that I did cry .

input: Yes, that was done.
target: Yes , that thou didst .

input: Did you ever see anything?
target: Didst thou see any thing ?

input: I don't know, nothing, my lord.
target: Nothing , my lord .

input: My lord, what are you saying?
target: My lord ?

input: My lord, what are you saying?
target: My lord ?

input: Why did you cry out in the middle of the night, sirs?
target: Why did you so cry out , sirs , in your sleep ?

input: Is it my lord that we did?
target: Did we , my lord ?

input: Ay is a word.
target: Ay .

input: Did you ever see anything?
target: Saw you anything ?

input: No, my lord, I did not see anything.
target: No , my lord , I saw nothing .

input: My lord, I am not.
target: Nor I , my lord .

input: Go and praise my brother, Cassius.
target: Go and commend me to my brother Cassius .

input: We will follow him if he is set on his powers before.
target: Bid him set on his powers betimes before , And we will follow .

input: My lord, it will be done, it will be done.
target: It shall be done , my lord .

input: Antony, our hopes are answered now.
target: Now , Antony , our hopes are answered .

input: You said the enemy wouldn't come down, but keep the hills and upper regions.
target: You said the enemy would not come down But keep the hills and upper regions .

input: It proves that isn't the case.
target: It proves not so .

input: Their battles are close to being over.
target: Their battles are at hand .

input: They want to warn us at Philippi before we demand them.
target: They mean to warn us at Philippi here , Answering before we do demand of them .

input: I am in their bosoms, and I know where they do it.
target: Tut , I am in their bosoms , and I know Wherefore they do it .

input: They could be content to visit other places, and come down with fear, thinking that they have courage.
target: They could be content To visit other places , and come down With fearful bravery , thinking by this face To fasten in our thoughts that they have courage .

input: But 'tis not true.
target: But 'tis not so .

input: Prepare you, generals.
target: Prepare you , generals .

input: The enemy comes on in a show.
target: The enemy comes on in gallant show .

input: Something to be done immediately after their bloody sign of battle was hung out.
target: Their bloody sign of battle is hung out , And something to be done immediately .

input: Upon the left hand of the even field Octavius, lead your battle softly.
target: Octavius , lead your battle softly on , Upon the left hand of the even field .

input: I handed it to the right hand.
target: Upon the right hand I .

input: The left is where you should keep the left.
target: Keep thou the left .

input: Why did you cross me in this exigent?
target: Why do you cross me in this exigent ?

input: They would have parley if they were standing.
target: They stand and would have parley .

input: Stand fast, Titinius.
target: Stand fast , Titinius .

input: We need to talk and out.
target: We must out and talk .

input: Is Mark Antony going to give a sign of battle?
target: Mark Antony , shall we give sign of battle ?

input: No, Caesar, we will respond to their charge.
target: No , Caesar , we will answer on their charge .

input: Make something happen.
target: Make forth .

input: The generals would have some things to say.
target: The generals would have some words .

input: Words are spoken before a blow.
target: Words before blows .

input: Is it true for you, countrymen?
target: Is it so , countrymen ?

input: We do not love words better than you do.
target: Not that we love words better , as you do .

input: Octavius said good words are better than bad strokes.
target: Good words are better than bad strokes , Octavius .

input: You give good words when you have bad strokes, Brutus.
target: In your bad strokes , Brutus , you give good words .

input: They rob the bees and leave them without honey.
target: But for your words , they rob the Hybla bees And leave them honeyless .

input: Not stingless as well?
target: Not stingless too ?

input: When your daggers Hacked one another in the side of Caesar, you did not do that.
target: Villains , you did not so when your vile daggers Hacked one another in the sides of Caesar .

input: Thank you, Flatterers, now, Brutus.
target: Flatterers ? , Now , Brutus , thank yourself .

input: The sword goes up again when you think about it.
target: When think you that the sword goes up again ?

input: Until Caesar's three and thirty wounds are avenged, or until another Caesar adds slaughter to the sword of traitors, never.
target: Never , till Caesar's three and thirty wounds Be well avenged , or till another Caesar Have added slaughter to the sword of traitors .

input: Unless Caesar brings them with him, he will not die by traitors' hands.
target: Caesar , thou canst not die by traitors ' hands Unless thou bring'st them with thee .

input: I hope that is the case.
target: So I hope .

input: I was not born to die on the sword.
target: I was not born to die on Brutus ' sword .

input: Young man, you could not die more honorable, if you wert the noblest of your strain.
target: O , if thou wert the noblest of thy strain , Young man , thou couldst not die more honorable .

input: A peevish schoolboy, worthless of such honor, joined with a masker and a reveler.
target: A peevish schoolboy , worthless of such honor , Joined with a masker and a reveler !

input: The old Cassius is still around.
target: Old Cassius still .

input: Come to the field if you want to fight today.
target: If you dare fight today , come to the field .

input: If you have stomachs, you should.
target: If not , when you have stomachs .

input: Why blow wind, swell billow, and swim bark now.
target: Why , now , blow wind , swell billow , and swim bark !

input: The storm is over and there is nothing left to do.
target: The storm is up and all is on the hazard .

input: A Messala!
target: Messala !

input: This is Messala's birthday, as this was the day when Cassius was born.
target: Messala , This is my birthday , as this very day Was Cassius born .

input: Messala, please give me your hand.
target: Give me thy hand , Messala .

input: I am compelled to set upon one battle all our liberties, if I witness that against my will, as Pompey was.
target: Be thou my witness that against my will , As Pompey was , am I compelled to set Upon one battle all our liberties .

input: I held him strong and his opinion was his.
target: You know that I held Epicurus strong And his opinion .

input: I changed my mind partly because of things that do presage.
target: Now I change my mind , And partly credit things that do presage .

input: Two mighty eagles fell from Sardis, and there they perched, feeding from the hands of our soldiers, who consorted with them.
target: Coming from Sardis , on our former ensign Two mighty eagles fell , and there they perched , Gorging and feeding from our soldiers ' hands , Who to Philippi here consorted us .

input: They fled away this morning, and in their steads do ravens, crows, and kites, as we were sickly prey.
target: This morning are they fled away and gone , And in their steads do ravens , crows , and kites Fly o'er our heads and downward look on us As we were sickly prey .

input: Our army is ready to give up the ghost, under their shadows.
target: Their shadows seem A canopy most fatal , under which Our army lies , ready to give up the ghost .

input: Don't believe that.
target: Believe not so .

input: I believe that I am fresh of spirit and resolved to meet all perils very frequently.
target: I but believe it partly , For I am fresh of spirit and resolved To meet all perils very constantly .

input: The gods stand friendly that we may, Lovers in peace, lead on our days to age.
target: Now , most noble Brutus , The gods today stand friendly that we may , Lovers in peace , lead on our days to age .

input: Since the affairs of men are still uncertain, let's reason with the worst that may happen.
target: But since the affairs of men rest still incertain , Let's reason with the worst that may befall .

input: If we lose this battle, is this the last time we will speak together?
target: If we do lose this battle , then is this The very last time we shall speak together .

input: What are you going to do after that?
target: What are you then determined to do ?

input: As soon as "Caesar" is born, "Brutus" will begin a spirit.
target: Brutus" will start a spirit as soon as "Caesar." Now in the names of all the gods at once , Upon what meat doth this our Caesar feed That he is grown so great ?

input: The art was shamed by the age.
target: Age , thou art shamed !

input: Rome, you have lost the nobility of noble bloods.
target: Rome , thou hast lost the breed of noble bloods !

input: It was famed with more than one man, since the great flood, when went there by an age.
target: When went there by an age , since the great flood , But it was famed with more than with one man ?

input: When did they say that her wide walks encompassed only one man?
target: When could they say till now , that talked of Rome , That her wide walks encompassed but one man ?

input: Is it Rome, and room enough, when there is only one man in it?
target: Now is it Rome indeed , and room enough , When there is in it but one only man .

input: Our fathers have said that there was a Brutus who would have brooked the eternal devil to keep his state in Rome as easily as a king.
target: Oh , you and I have heard our fathers say , There was a Brutus once that would have brooked Th ' eternal devil to keep his state in Rome As easily as a king .

input: I am not jealous that you do love me.
target: That you do love me , I am nothing jealous .

input: I have an aim, what you would do for me is something I want.
target: What you would work me to , I have some aim .

input: I will recount how I have thought about this and these times.
target: How I have thought of this and of these times I shall recount hereafter .

input: I would not be able to do that for this present, so with love I would ask you to be more moved.
target: For this present , I would not , so with love I might entreat you , Be any further moved .

input: I will consider what you have said, what you have to say, and find a time for both of them to meet to hear and answer such high things.
target: What you have said I will consider , what you have to say I will with patience hear , and find a time Both meet to hear and answer such high things .

input: Brutus had rather be a villager than to himself a son of Rome under these hard conditions, as this time Is like to lay upon us.
target: Till then , my noble friend , chew upon this : Brutus had rather be a villager Than to repute himself a son of Rome Under these hard conditions as this time Is like to lay upon us .

input: I am happy that my weak words have struck and caused a show of fire from Brutus.
target: I am glad that my weak words Have struck but thus much show of fire from Brutus .

input: If we lose this battle, you will be happy to be led in triumph in the streets of Rome.
target: Then if we lose this battle You are contented to be led in triumph Thorough the streets of Rome ?

input: No, Cassius, no.
target: No , Cassius , no .

input: Think not, Roman, that ever Brutus will go bound to Rome.
target: Think not , thou noble Roman , That ever Brutus will go bound to Rome .

input: He has a mind that is too great.
target: He bears too great a mind .

input: We will take our farewell take.
target: Therefore our everlasting farewell take .

input: It was forever and forever farewell, Cassius.
target: Forever and forever farewell , Cassius .

input: If we do meet again, we will smile.
target: If we do meet again , why , we shall smile .

input: This parting was made well if not if not.
target: If not , why then this parting was well made .

input: It is forever and forever farewell, Brutus.
target: Forever and forever farewell , Brutus .

input: We will smile if we do meet again.
target: If we do meet again , we'll smile indeed .

input: This parting was well made if not, 'tis true.
target: If not , 'tis true this parting was well made .

input: Why do you want to lead on.
target: Why then , lead on .

input: The end of this day's business will come, that's what a man might know.
target: Oh , that a man might know The end of this day's business ere it come !

input: The day will end, and then the end is known.
target: But it sufficeth that the day will end , And then the end is known. , Come , ho !

input: Away from you!
target: Away !

input: Ride, ride, Messala, ride, and give these bills to the legions on the other side.
target: Ride , ride , Messala , ride , and give these bills Unto the legions on the other side .

input: Let them set on at once, for I think Octavius' demeanor is cold, and sudden push gives them the overthrow.
target: Let them set on at once , for I perceive But cold demeanor in Octavius ' wing , And sudden push gives them the overthrow .

input: Messala, ride, ride, ride.
target: Ride , ride , Messala .

input: I have to turn my enemy into my own.
target: Myself have to mine own turned enemy .

input: O Brutus, who had an advantage on Octavius, gave the word too early, and took it too eagerly.
target: O Cassius , Brutus gave the word too early , Who , having some advantage on Octavius , Took it too eagerly .

input: Fly further off, my lord.
target: Fly further off , my lord , fly further off .

input: My lord, Mark Antony is in your tents.
target: Mark Antony is in your tents , my lord .

input: Fly, therefore, noble Cassius, fly far away.
target: Fly , therefore , noble Cassius , fly far off .

input: Is the fire in those tents where I view it?
target: Are those my tents where I perceive the fire ?

input: My lord, they are, they are.
target: They are , my lord .

input: Titinius, if you love me, mount my horse, and hide my spurs in him, I will be sure that yond troops are friends or enemies.
target: Titinius , if thou lovest me , Mount thou my horse , and hide thy spurs in him Till he have brought thee up to yonder troops And here again , that I may rest assured Whether yond troops are friend or enemy .

input: Even though I have a thought, I will be here again.
target: I will be here again , even with a thought .

input: Go, Pindarus, get higher on that hill.
target: Go , Pindarus , get higher on that hill .

input: My sight was so thick that I couldn't see anything.
target: My sight was ever thick .

input: Titinius, please tell me what you observe about the field.
target: Regard Titinius , And tell me what thou notest about the field .

input: I breathed the first thing this day.
target: This day I breathed first .

input: There will be time coming round and where I started, there will be time to end.
target: Time is come round , And where I did begin , there shall I end .

input: My life is determined by his compass.
target: My life is run his compass .

input: What is the latest news?
target: What news ?

input: And, I think.
target: And , hark !

input: They shout for happiness.
target: They shout for joy .

input: Come down, you will see no more.
target: Come down , behold no more .

input: To live so long to see my best friend before my eyes!
target: Oh , coward that I am , to live so long To see my best friend ta'en before my face !

input: Sirrah, come hither.
target: Come hither , sirrah .

input: Come now and keep your oath.
target: Come now , keep thine oath .

input: Even with the sword that killed thee, Caesar was revenged.
target: Caesar , thou art revenged , Even with the sword that killed thee .

input: I am free now.
target: So I am free .

input: I have done my will, so wouldn't that have been?
target: Yet would not so have been , Durst I have done my will .

input: Pindarus will run far from this country, where never Roman will take notice of him.
target: O Cassius , Far from this country Pindarus shall run , Where never Roman shall take note of him .

input: Titinius, for Octavius Is overthrown by noble Brutus'power', as Cassius'legions are by Antony'.
target: It is but change , Titinius , for Octavius Is overthrown by noble Brutus ' power , As Cassius ' legions are by Antony .

input: These tidings will be comforting for Cassius.
target: These tidings will well comfort Cassius .

input: What place did you leave him?
target: Where did you leave him ?

input: All disconsolate, with Pindarus his bondman on this hill.
target: All disconsolate , With Pindarus his bondman on this hill .

input: Is it not that he lies on the ground.
target: Is not that he that lies upon the ground ?

input: He does not lie like the living does.
target: He lies not like the living .

input: My heart, O!
target: O my heart !

input: Is it not that he?
target: Is not that he ?

input: Pindarus, what are you talking about?
target: What , Pindarus !

input: Where is the art of Pindarus?
target: Where art thou , Pindarus ?

input: Seek him, Titinius, while I go to meet The noble Brutus, and thrust this report into his ears.
target: Seek him , Titinius , whilst I go to meet The noble Brutus , thrusting this report Into his ears .

input: I can say that piercing steel and darts will be as welcome to the ears of Brutus as the sight is.
target: I may say "thrusting" it , For piercing steel and darts envenomed Shall be as welcome to the ears of Brutus As tidings of this sight .

input: I will be looking for Pindarus while you are there.
target: Hie you , Messala , And I will seek for Pindarus the while .

input: Is it because I was brave Cassius that he sent me forth?
target: Why didst thou send me forth , brave Cassius ?

input: I don't know if I didn't meet my friends.
target: Did I not meet thy friends ?

input: They put on my brow a wreath of victory, but did not give it to me.
target: And did not they Put on my brows this wreath of victory And bid me give it thee ?

input: Is it possible that they didn't hear their shouts.
target: Didst thou not hear their shouts ?

input: Alas, thou hast misconstrued everything.
target: Alas , thou hast misconstrued everything !

input: But, hold thee, take this garland on your brow.
target: But , hold thee , take this garland on thy brow .

input: I will do his bidding after he bid me give it to him.
target: Thy Brutus bid me give it thee , and I Will do his bidding .

input: Where is Messala, where is his body lying?
target: Where , where , Messala , doth his body lie ?

input: Titinius and yonder were mourning it.
target: Lo , yonder , and Titinius mourning it .

input: Titinius has a face that is upward.
target: Titinius ' face is upward .

input: He is no longer alive.
target: He is slain .

input: O Julius Caesar, you are mighty yet.
target: O Julius Caesar , thou art mighty yet !

input: In our own proper entrails, our spirit walks abroad and turns our swords.
target: Thy spirit walks abroad and turns our swords In our own proper entrails .

input: Is there more than two Romans living like these?
target: Are yet two Romans living such as these ?

input: The last of all the Romans, well done!
target: The last of all the Romans , fare thee well !

input: I am going to find time, Cassius.
target: I shall find time , Cassius , I shall find time .

input: Thasos should come and send his body.
target: Come , therefore , and to Thasos send his body .

input: We are going to the field.
target: Let us to the field .

input: Labio and Flavio were the ones who started our battles.
target: Labio and Flavio , set our battles on .

input: We shall try fortune in a second fight after three o'clock.
target: Tis three o'clock , and , Romans , yet ere night We shall try fortune in a second fight .

input: What does the bastard do not do?
target: What bastard doth not ?

input: Who will accompany me?
target: Who will go with me ?

input: My name will be announced about the field.
target: I will proclaim my name about the field .

input: I am the son of a man named Marcus.
target: I am the son of Marcus Cato , ho !

input: A foe to tyrants and a friend to my country.
target: A foe to tyrants , and my country's friend .

input: I am the son of a man named Marcus.
target: I am the son of Marcus Cato , ho !

input: I'm Marcus Brutus, and I'm also known as Brutus.
target: And I am Brutus , Marcus Brutus , I !

input: My country's friend is called Brutus.
target: Brutus , my country's friend .

input: You should know me for Brutus.
target: Know me for Brutus !

input: Is it true that the young and noble Cato is art thou down?
target: O young and noble Cato , art thou down ?

input: Only I will die.
target: Only I yield to die .

input: There is so much that I will be killed straight away.
target: There is so much that thou wilt kill me straight .

input: If you want to be remembered in his death, kill Brutus.
target: Kill Brutus , and be honored in his death .

input: We must not do that.
target: We must not .

input: A person who is a noble prisoner.
target: A noble prisoner !

input: It's a room, ho!
target: Room , ho !

input: Tell Antony Brutus that he's alive.
target: Tell Antony Brutus is ta'en .

input: I'll let you know about the news.
target: I'll tell the news .

input: Where is he located?
target: Where is he ?

input: I am safe, Antony.
target: Safe , Antony .

input: I assure thee that no enemy will ever take alive the noble Brutus.
target: I dare assure thee that no enemy Shall ever take alive the noble Brutus .

input: He was defended from so great a shame by the gods.
target: The gods defend him from so great a shame !

input: Caesar is coming back after the games are done.
target: The games are done and Caesar is returning .

input: As they pass by, take Casca by the sleeve, and he will tell you what happened today.
target: As they pass by , pluck Casca by the sleeve , And he will , after his sour fashion , tell you What hath proceeded worthy note today .

input: I will do that.
target: I will do so .

input: The angry spot on Caesar's brow glows, and all the rest look like a hidden train.
target: But , look you , Cassius , The angry spot doth glow on Caesar's brow , And all the rest look like a chidden train .

input: Calphurnia's cheek is pale, and Cicero looks with a ferret and fiery eyes, as we have seen him in the Capitol.
target: Calphurnia's cheek is pale , and Cicero Looks with such ferret and such fiery eyes As we have seen him in the Capitol Being crossed in conference by some senators .

input: The matter will be given to us by Casca.
target: Casca will tell us what the matter is .

input: The man is named Antonio.
target: Antonio .

input: Caesar is a person.
target: Caesar .

input: Rest on this rock, poor remains of friends, come.
target: Come , poor remains of friends , rest on this rock .

input: Statilius showed the torchlight, but my lord, He didn't come back.
target: Statilius showed the torchlight but , my lord , He came not back .

input: He is either dead or alive.
target: He is or ta'en or slain .

input: Clitus, Sit thee down.
target: Sit thee down , Clitus .

input: Clitus, Hark thee.
target: Hark thee , Clitus .

input: I, my lord, what are you talking about?
target: What , I , my lord ?

input: It's not for all of the world.
target: No , not for all the world .

input: It is time for peace then!
target: Peace then !

input: There were no words.
target: No words .

input: I'll kill myself if that's what it takes.
target: I'll rather kill myself .

input: Hark thee and Dardanius.
target: Hark thee , Dardanius .

input: Is it possible that I will do such a deed?
target: Shall I do such a deed ?

input: O Dardanius, greetings!
target: O Dardanius !

input: O Clitus!
target: O Clitus !

input: Volumnius, come hither, good.
target: Come hither , good Volumnius .

input: There is a word to list.
target: List a word .

input: What does my lord tell me?
target: What says my lord ?

input: This last night in the fields of Sardis was the last one.
target: At Sardis once , And this last night here in Philippi fields .

input: I know my hour is coming.
target: I know my hour is come .

input: My lord, not so, that's right.
target: Not so , my lord .

input: I am pretty sure it is, Volumnius.
target: Nay , I am sure it is , Volumnius .

input: How it goes, Volumnius, you are the one who sees the world.
target: Thou seest the world , Volumnius , how it goes .

input: Our enemies beat us to the pits.
target: Our enemies have beat us to the pit .

input: It is more appropriate to leap in ourselves than tarry until they push us.
target: It is more worthy to leap in ourselves Than tarry till they push us .

input: We went to school together, good Volumnius.
target: Good Volumnius , Thou know'st that we two went to school together .

input: I prithee, hold my sword hilts, while I run on it, for our love of old.
target: Even for that our love of old , I prithee , Hold thou my sword hilts , whilst I run on it .

input: That isn't an office for a friend, my lord.
target: That's not an office for a friend , my lord .

input: My lord, fly, fly.
target: Fly , fly , my lord .

input: There is no tarrying in this area.
target: There is no tarrying here .

input: Volumnius, farewell to you.
target: Farewell to you. , And you. , And you , Volumnius .
Strato , thou hast been all this while asleep .

input: By this vile conquest, I will have more glory than Octavius and Mark Antony did.
target: I shall have glory by this losing day More than Octavius and Mark Antony By this vile conquest shall attain unto .

input: For Hath almost ended his life's history, so fare you well at the same time.
target: So fare you well at once , for Brutus ' tongue Hath almost ended his life's history .

input: Night is hanging upon my eyes.
target: Night hangs upon mine eyes .

input: My bones would rest, that they have labored to achieve this hour.
target: My bones would rest , That have but labored to attain this hour .

input: Fly, my lord, fly.
target: Fly , my lord , fly .

input: Therefore.
target: Hence .

input: I will be following.
target: I will follow .

input: I prithee, stay by the lord.
target: I prithee , Strato , stay thou by thy lord .

input: Thou art a fellow who respects you.
target: Thou art a fellow of a good respect .

input: There was a match of honor in the life of the person.
target: Thy life hath had some smatch of honor in it .

input: While I run upon it, turn away my sword and hold it.
target: Hold then my sword and turn away thy face While I do run upon it .

input: Is there any truth to the rumor that Strato is Wilt thou?
target: Wilt thou , Strato ?

input: Give me your hand first, then I'll give you the rest.
target: Give me your hand first .

input: Good farewell, good Strato.
target: Farewell , good Strato .

input: What is that man doing?
target: What man is that ?

input: Messala is free from the bondage you are in.
target: Free from the bondage you are in , Messala .

input: I will entertain them all that was served to Brutus.
target: All that served Brutus , I will entertain them .

input: Is it possible that you grant me time with me?
target: Fellow , wilt thou bestow thy time with me ?

input: Messala will prefer me to you, if that's true.
target: Ay , if Messala will prefer me to you .

input: Good Messala, please do so.
target: Do so , good Messala .

input: What happened to my master, Strato?
target: How died my master , Strato ?

input: I held the sword and he ran after it.
target: I held the sword and he did run on it .

input: The latest service to my master was done by Octavius after he took him to follow thee.
target: Octavius , then take him to follow thee , That did the latest service to my master .

input: The noblest Roman of them all was this one.
target: This was the noblest Roman of them all .

input: All the conspirators saved only he, because they were jealous of great Caesar.
target: All the conspirators save only he Did that they did in envy of great Caesar .

input: He made one of them because he was honest and common good to everyone.
target: He only in a general honest thought And common good to all , made one of them .

input: According to his virtue, let us use him and say to all the world, "This was a man." His life was gentle and the elements were mixed in him.
target: His life was gentle , and the elements So mixed in him that Nature might stand up And say to all the world , "This was a man." According to his virtue let us use him , With all respect and rites of burial .

input: His bones tonight will be most like a soldier, ordered honorably.
target: Within my tent his bones tonight shall lie Most like a soldier , ordered honorably .

input: Call the field to rest, and let's go away and enjoy this happy day.
target: So call the field to rest , and let's away To part the glories of this happy day .

input: Casca and Ay are the same.
target: Ay , Casca .

input: Caesar looks sad, tell us what happened today.
target: Tell us what hath chanced today That Caesar looks so sad .

input: Were you not with him, why?
target: Why , you were with him , were you not ?

input: I don't want to ask Casca what happened.
target: I should not then ask Casca what had chanced .

input: The crown was offered to him and he put it by with the back of his hand, as the people fell a-shouting.
target: Why , there was a crown offered him ; and , being offered him , he put it by with the back of his hand , thus ; and then the people fell a-shouting .

input: What was the second noise for?
target: What was the second noise for ?

input: Why, for that as well.
target: Why , for that too .

input: They shouted a number of times.
target: They shouted thrice .

input: What was the last thing that the person said?
target: What was the last cry for ?

input: Why, for that as well.
target: Why , for that too .

input: Was the crown offering him more than one time?
target: Was the crown offered him thrice ?

input: Ay, marry, was 't, and he put it by three times, every time gentle than other, and at every putting-by mine honest neighbors shouted.
target: Ay , marry , was 't , and he put it by thrice , every time gentler than other , and at every putting-by mine honest neighbors shouted .

input: He was offered the crown by someone.
target: Who offered him the crown ?

input: Antony asked why.
target: Why , Antony .

input: Tell us how it happened.
target: Tell us the manner of it , gentle Casca .

input: I can be hanged as well as tell the manner of it.
target: I can as well be hanged as tell the manner of it .

input: I saw Mark Antony offer him a crown, but it wasn't one of these coronets, and he put it by once, to my thinking.
target: I saw Mark Antony offer him a crown ( yet 'twas not a crown neither , 'twas one of these coronets ) and , as I told you , he put it by once , but , for all that , to my thinking , he would fain have had it .

input: He offered it to him again, then he put it by again, but to my thinking, he was very reluctant to let go of it.
target: Then he offered it to him again , then he put it by again , but , to my thinking , he was very loath to lay his fingers off it .

input: And then he offered it again.
target: And then he offered it the third time .

input: I don't laugh for fear of opening my lips and getting bad air, for my own part.
target: And for mine own part , I durst not laugh for fear of opening my lips and receiving the bad air .

input: I am praying for you, but soft.
target: But soft , I pray you .

input: What did Caesar do that made him blush?
target: What , did Caesar swoon ?

input: He was speechless after he fell down in the marketplace.
target: He fell down in the marketplace , and foamed at mouth , and was speechless .

input: It is very similar.
target: Tis very like .

input: The falling sickness is what he has.
target: He hath the falling sickness .

input: No, Caesar did not do that.
target: No , Caesar hath it not .

input: We have the falling sickness, but you and I are both honest.
target: But you and I And honest Casca , we have the falling sickness .

input: I'm not sure what you mean by that, but I'm pretty sure Caesar fell down.
target: I know not what you mean by that , but I am sure Caesar fell down .

input: He came unto himself, what did he say to himself?
target: What said he when he came unto himself ?

input: Before he fell down, he plucked me from his doublet and offered them his throat to cut, because he thought the common herd was happy he refused the crown.
target: Marry , before he fell down , when he perceived the common herd was glad he refused the crown , he plucked me ope his doublet and offered them his throat to cut .

input: I would go to hell if I had not taken him at a word, I had been a man of any occupation.
target: An I had been a man of any occupation , if I would not have taken him at a word , I would I might go to hell among the rogues .

input: And then he fell.
target: And so he fell .

input: He wanted their worships to think it was his infirmity when he came to himself again, if he had done or said anything amiss.
target: When he came to himself again , he said , if he had done or said anything amiss , he desired their worships to think it was his infirmity .

input: I cried, "Alas, good soul", and they forgave him with all of their hearts.
target: Three or four wenches where I stood cried , "Alas , good soul ! " and forgave him with all their hearts .

input: If Caesar had stabbed their mothers, they would have done the same thing.
target: If Caesar had stabbed their mothers they would have done no less .

input: He came away sad after that.
target: And after that he came thus sad away ?

input: Ay is a word.
target: Ay .

input: Therefore!
target: Hence !

input: Home, you idling creatures get you home.
target: Home , you idle creatures get you home !

input: This is a holiday, is it?
target: Is this a holiday ?

input: Why, sir, I am a carpenter.
target: Why , sir , a carpenter .

input: Where is her leather apron and her rule?
target: Where is thy leather apron and thy rule ?

input: What do you think about the best apparel on the market?
target: What dost thou with thy best apparel on ?

input: In respect of a fine workman, I am but a cobbler, as you would say, sir.
target: Truly , sir , in respect of a fine workman , I am but , as you would say , a cobbler .

input: What trade art are you talking about.
target: But what trade art thou ?

input: I would like to know if you answered me directly.
target: Answer me directly .

input: A trade, sir, that I hope I may use with a safe conscience, which is, indeed, sir, a mender of bad soles.
target: A trade , sir , that I hope I may use with a safe conscience , which is , indeed , sir , a mender of bad soles .

input: What trade are you talking about, knave?
target: What trade , thou knave ?

input: Thou naughty knave, what trade is it?
target: Thou naughty knave , what trade ?

input: I plead with you to not be with me.
target: Nay , I beseech you , sir , be not out with me .

input: If you're out, I can make you better.
target: Yet , if you be out , sir , I can mend you .

input: What does it mean by that?
target: What mean'st thou by that ?

input: Is it possible that I'm male and he's saucy fellow?
target: Mend" me , thou saucy fellow ?

input: Cicero did not say anything.
target: Did Cicero say anything ?

input: He spoke a language that was Greek.
target: Ay , he spoke Greek .

input: What effect does it have?
target: To what effect ?

input: I will look you in the face again, I tell you that.
target: Nay , an I tell you that , I'll ne'er look you i ' th ' face again .

input: Those that understood him smiled at one another and shook their heads.
target: But those that understood him smiled at one another and shook their heads .

input: It was Greek for me, for my own part.
target: But , for mine own part , it was Greek to me .

input: I could give you more information.
target: I could tell you more news too .

input: Murellus and Flavius were put to silence for pulling scarfs off Caesar's pictures.
target: Murellus and Flavius , for pulling scarfs off Caesar's images , are put to silence .

input: Well done, Fare you well.
target: Fare you well .

input: If I could remember it, there was more foolery going on.
target: There was more foolery yet , if I could remember it .

input: Will you be with me tonight, Casca?
target: Will you sup with me tonight , Casca ?

input: I will be promised again.
target: No , I am promised forth .

input: Will you join me for dinner tomorrow?
target: Will you dine with me tomorrow ?

input: If I'm alive and you're still alive, your dinner is worth the eating.
target: Ay , if I be alive and your mind hold and your dinner worth the eating .

input: Good, that's right.
target: Good .

input: I will expect you to do the right thing.
target: I will expect you .

input: Do this.
target: Do so .

input: Both of them will be farewelling.
target: Farewell both .

input: This man is grown to be a very blunt fellow.
target: What a blunt fellow is this grown to be !

input: When he went to school, he was quick to respond.
target: He was quick mettle when he went to school .

input: He puts on this tardy form, but is he now in execution of any bold or noble enterprise.
target: So is he now in execution Of any bold or noble enterprise , However he puts on this tardy form .

input: This rudeness is a sauce to his good wit, which makes men stomach to digest his words.
target: This rudeness is a sauce to his good wit , Which gives men stomach to digest his words With better appetite .

input: And so it is as well.
target: And so it is .

input: For this time, I will not be with you.
target: For this time I will leave you .

input: If you want to speak with me tomorrow, I will come back to you.
target: Tomorrow , if you please to speak with me , I will come home to you .

input: If you will, come home to me and I will wait for you.
target: Or , if you will , Come home to me , and I will wait for you .

input: I will do that.
target: I will do so .

input: Don't think of the world until then.
target: Till then , think of the world .

input: Well, Brutus, you are an art noble.
target: Well , Brutus , thou art noble .

input: Caesar does not like me, but he loves me.
target: Caesar doth bear me hard , but he loves Brutus .

input: He should not make fun of me if I were Brutus and he were Cassius.
target: If I were Brutus now and he were Cassius , He should not humor me .

input: I will this night, in several hands, in at his windows throw, as if they came from several citizens. Writings all tending to the great opinion that Rome holds of his name, and obscurely Caesar's ambition shall be glanced at.
target: I will this night , In several hands , in at his windows throw , As if they came from several citizens , Writings all tending to the great opinion That Rome holds of his name , wherein obscurely Caesar's ambition shall be glanced at .

input: Either there is a civil war in heaven or the world is too friendly with the gods to cause destruction.

target: But men may construe things after their fashion , Clean from the purpose of the things themselves .

target: Our yoke and sufferance show us womanish .

input: But life, being weary of these worldly bars, never lacks power to dismiss itself.
target: But life , being weary of these worldly bars , Never lacks power to dismiss itself .

target: He were no lion were not Romans hinds .

target: Am I not stayed for , Cinna ?

target: I am glad on 't .

target: How that might change his nature , there's the question .

input: The closet is where the taper burneth, sir.
target: The taper burneth in your closet , sir .

input: You should get to bed again.

target: It is not day .

target: Count the clock .

target: We'll leave you , Brutus .

target: But all remember What you have said , and show yourselves true Romans .

target: Boy !

input: Is fast asleep Lucius?
target: Lucius ! , Fast asleep ?

target: It is no matter .

input: Enjoy the honey and sleep well.
target: Enjoy the honey-heavy dew of slumber .

target: Therefore thou sleep'st so sound .

input: My lord, my friend, my friend, my friend, my friend, my friend, my friend, my friend, my friend, my friend, my friend, my friend, my friend, my friend, my friend, my friend, my friend, my friend, my friend, my
target: Brutus , my lord .

input: What do you mean by what you say?
target: Portia , what mean you ?

target: It is not for your health thus to commit Your weak condition to the raw , cold morning .

target: Nor for yours neither .

target: Y ' have ungently , Brutus , Stole from my bed .

target: Go , go , good countrymen , and for this fault , Assemble all the poor men of your sort , Draw them to Tiber banks , and weep your tears Into the channel till the lowest stream Do kiss the most exalted shores of all .
