input: Was never a widow who had so much to lose.
target: Was never widow had so dear a loss .

input: They were never orphans, but they were very dear to the loss.
target: Were never orphans had so dear a loss .

input: It was never mother's loss that was so dear to her.
target: Was never mother had so dear a loss .

input: I am the mother of those griefs.
target: Alas , I am the mother of these griefs .

input: She weeps for Edward and so do I, but she doesn't weep for Clarence.
target: She for an Edward weeps , and so do I ; I for a Clarence weep ; so doth not she .

input: These babes for Clarence weep, so do I, and so do Edward, so do not they.
target: These babes for Clarence weep and so do I ; I for an Edward weep ; so do not they .

input: You should be like a careful mother, Of the young prince your son.
target: Madam , bethink you , like a careful mother , Of the young prince your son .

input: In him, you have your comfort lives.
target: In him your comfort lives .

input: Sister, please have comfort.
target: Sister , have comfort .

input: None of us can help our harms by wailing them. I did not see your Grace.
target: All of us have cause To wail the dimming of our shining star , But none can help our harms by wailing them. , Madam , my mother , I do cry you mercy ; I did not see your Grace .

input: I crave your blessing on my knee, it's terrible.
target: Humbly on my knee I crave your blessing .

input: Put meekness in her breast, love, charity, and true duty, and God bless thee.
target: God bless thee , and put meekness in thy breast , Love , charity , obedience , and true duty .

input: You cloudy princes and heart-sorrowing peers, now cheer each other in each other's love, because they bear this heavy mutual load of moan.
target: You cloudy princes and heart-sorrowing peers That bear this heavy mutual load of moan , Now cheer each other in each other's love .

input: We are going to reap the harvest of his son, even though we have spent our harvest of this king.
target: Though we have spent our harvest of this king , We are to reap the harvest of his son .

input: The broken rancor of your high-swoll'n hates, but lately splintered, knit, and joined together, must be gently preserved, cherished, and kept.
target: The broken rancor of your high-swoll'n hates , But lately splintered , knit , and joined together , Must gently be preserved , cherished , and kept .

input: To be crowned our king, the young prince would have to travel on a little train from Ludlow to London.
target: Meseemeth good that with some little train Forthwith from Ludlow the young prince be fet Hither to London , to be crowned our king .

input: My Lord of Buckingham, why did you use a little train?
target: Why "with some little train , " my Lord of Buckingham ?

input: I hope the king made peace with us all, and that the compact is true in me.
target: I hope the king made peace with all of us ; And the compact is firm and true in me .

input: I think that in me and so in all.
target: And so in me , and so , I think , in all .

input: It is meet so few should fetch the prince, that's what I said to noble Buckingham.
target: Therefore I say with noble Buckingham That it is meet so few should fetch the prince .

input: And so I say that.
target: And so say I .

input: For God's sake, let us not have two at home, my lord, whoever goes to the prince.
target: My lord , whoever journeys to the prince , For God's sake let not us two at home .

input: To part the queen's proud kindred from the prince is an index to the story we late talked about.
target: For by the way I'll sort occasion , As index to the story we late talked of , To part the queen's proud kindred from the prince .

input: My other self, my oracle, my prophet, my cousin, and I, as a child, will not stay behind, for we will go by the direction of Ludlow.
target: My other self , my council's consistory , My oracle , my prophet , my dear cousin , I , as a child , will go by thy direction Toward Ludlow then , for we'll not stay behind .

input: Good tomorrow, neighbor, MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE MzE
target: Good morrow , neighbor , whither away so fast ?

input: I promise you that I don't know much about myself.
target: I promise you I scarcely know myself .

input: Do you know about the news abroad.
target: Hear you the news abroad ?

input: Yes, the king is no longer alive.
target: Yes , that the king is dead .

input: God speed and neighbors.
target: Neighbors , God speed .

input: Sir, give you good news tomorrow.
target: Give you good morrow , sir .

input: Is the news of good King Edward's death still true?
target: Doth this news hold of good King Edward's death ?

input: Ay, sir, it's too true, please help the while.
target: Ay , sir , it is too true , God help the while .

input: Then, masters, look to see a world that is not perfect.
target: Then , masters , look to see a troublous world .

input: No, by God's good grace, his son will rule.
target: No , no , by God's good grace , his son shall reign .

input: There's a land that's governed by a child.
target: Woe to the land that's governed by a child .

input: In him there is a hope of government, which in his nonage, council under him, and in his full and ripened years, himself, no doubt shall then govern well.
target: In him there is a hope of government , Which , in his nonage , council under him , And , in his full and ripened years , himself , No doubt shall then , and till then , govern well .

input: With patience, noble lord, prisoners must as well.
target: With patience , noble lord , as prisoners must .

input: The eagle should be mewed because kites and buzzards prey on liberty.
target: More pity that the eagle should be mewed While kites and buzzards prey at liberty .

input: What news is happening in other countries?
target: What news abroad ?

input: It is very grievous to be thinking about it.
target: Tis very grievous to be thought upon .

input: Where is he in his bedroom?
target: Where is he , in his bed ?

input: He is a person.
target: He is .

input: I will follow you after you go before.
target: Go you before , and I will follow you .

input: When Henry the Sixth was crowned in Paris at nine months old, the state stood still.
target: So stood the state when Henry the Sixth Was crowned in Paris but at nine months old .

input: Stood the state so?
target: Stood the state so ?

input: It would have been better if they came by his father, or by the father at all, for he would have been closest to us.
target: Better it were they all came by his father , Or by the father there were none at all , For emulation who shall now be nearest Will touch us all too near if God prevent not .

input: The duke of Gloucester is full of danger, and the queen's sons and brothers are haught and proud, so this sickly land might solace as before.
target: O , full of danger is the duke of Gloucester , And the queen's sons and brothers haught and proud , And were they to be ruled , and not to rule , This sickly land might solace as before .

input: Come, come, we fear the worst.
target: Come , come , we fear the worst .

input: All will be alright.
target: All will be well .

input: Men expect a shortage when storms are unpredictable.
target: Untimely storms make men expect a dearth .

input: All may be well, but if God sort it so, 'T is more than we deserve or I expect'.
target: All may be well ; but if God sort it so , 'T is more than we deserve or I expect .

input: Is it still that way before the days of change?
target: Before the days of change , still is it so .

input: Leave it all to the Almighty.
target: But leave it all to God .

input: Is it possible that she is away?
target: Whither away ?

input: We were sent to the justices to be married.
target: Marry , we were sent for to the justices .

input: They will be here tomorrow or the next day.
target: Tomorrow or next day they will be here .

input: I want to see the prince, that's what I want.
target: I long with all my heart to see the prince .

input: I hope he has grown since last time I saw him.
target: I hope he is much grown since last I saw him .

input: I wouldn't have it, Ay, mother.
target: Ay , mother , but I would not have it so .

input: Why is my young cousin here?
target: Why , my young cousin ?

input: It is a good thing to grow.
target: It is good to grow .

input: "Ay, quoth my uncle Gloucester, " great weeds do grow apace." And since, Grandam, one night as we did sit at supper, my uncle Rivers talked how I did grow more than my brother.
target: Grandam , one night as we did sit at supper , My uncle Rivers talked how I did grow More than my brother : "Ay , " quoth my uncle Gloucester , "Small herbs have grace ; great weeds do grow apace." And since , methinks I would not grow so fast Because sweet flowers are slow and weeds make haste .

input: Good faith, good faith, the saying did not hold in him that he objected to the same thing.
target: Good faith , good faith , the saying did not hold In him that did object the same to thee !

input: He was the worst thing to happen to him when he was young, so long a-growing and so leisurely, that if this rule were true, he should be gracious.
target: He was the wretched'st thing when he was young , So long a-growing and so leisurely , That if this rule were true , he should be gracious .

input: My gracious madam, he is, no doubt about it.
target: And so no doubt he is , my gracious madam .

input: I hope he is, but I don't want mothers to doubt him.
target: I hope he is , but yet let mothers doubt .

input: If I had been remembered, I could have given my uncle's permission to touch his growth closer than I did.
target: Now , by my troth , if I had been remembered , I could have given my uncle's grace a flout To touch his growth nearer than he touched mine .

input: How do I know my York is pretty?
target: How , my pretty York ?

input: Let me hear it, I prithee.
target: I prithee let me hear it .

input: They say my uncle was so fast growing that he could gnaw a crust in two hours.
target: Marry , they say my uncle grew so fast That he could gnaw a crust at two hours old .

input: I was able to get a tooth after two years.
target: Twas full two years ere I could get a tooth .

input: This would have been a biting joke, Grandam.
target: Grandam , this would have been a biting jest .

input: Who told thee this, I prithee, York?
target: I prithee , pretty York , who told thee this ?

input: He had a nurse, Grandam.
target: Grandam , his nurse .

input: His nurse, what?
target: His nurse ?

input: Why was she dead when she was born?
target: Why , she was dead ere thou wast born .

input: I can't tell who told me if she wasn't her.
target: If 'twere not she , I can not tell who told me .

input: A boy is not very good.
target: A parlous boy !

input: You are too smart to go to that.
target: Go to , you are too shrewd .

input: Be nice to the child and not angry with him.
target: Good madam , be not angry with the child .

input: There are ears for pitchers.
target: Pitchers have ears .

input: There is a messenger here.
target: Here comes a messenger .

input: What is the latest news?
target: What news ?

input: My lord, I grieve for you to report this news.
target: Such news , my lord , as grieves me to report .

input: How do the prince do his job?
target: How doth the prince ?

input: Well, madam, and in good health.
target: Well , madam , and in health .

input: What is the current news?
target: What is thy news then ?

input: The dukes are Buckingham, Gloucester and the mighty dukes.
target: The mighty dukes , Gloucester and Buckingham .

input: What is the offense?
target: For what offence ?

input: I have disclosed the total amount of all I can.
target: The sum of all I can , I have disclosed .

input: I don't know what the nobles were committed to, my gracious lord.
target: Why , or for what , the nobles were committed Is all unknown to me , my gracious lord .

input: I am Ay me!
target: Ay me !

input: I can see that my house has been destroyed.
target: I see the ruin of my house .

input: Welcome, destruction, blood, and slaughter.
target: Welcome , destruction , blood , and massacre .

input: My husband lost his life to get the crown, and often up and down my sons were tossed for me to joy and grieve.
target: My husband lost his life to get the crown , And often up and down my sons were tossed For me to joy , and weep , their gain and loss .

input: Let me die, to look on death no more, because of the preposterous and frantic outrage.
target: O , preposterous And frantic outrage , end thy damned spleen , Or let me die , to look on death no more .

input: You were melancholy because of the weary way.
target: The weary way hath made you melancholy .

input: No, uncle, but our crosses on the way have made it very tiring.
target: No , uncle , but our crosses on the way Have made it tedious , wearisome , and heavy .

input: I would like to have more uncles here to welcome me.
target: I want more uncles here to welcome me .

input: Those uncles which you want were dangerous.
target: Those uncles which you want were dangerous .

input: Your Grace looked not on the poison of their hearts, but on their words.
target: Your Grace attended to their sugared words But looked not on the poison of their hearts .

input: God keep you away from them and from false friends.
target: God keep you from them , and from such false friends .

input: They were not true friends, but God kept me from them.
target: God keep me from false friends , but they were none .

input: The mayor of London is here to welcome you.
target: My lord , the mayor of London comes to greet you .

input: God bless your Grace with good health and happy days.
target: God bless your Grace with health and happy days .

input: Hastings doesn't come to tell us whether they will come or not.
target: Fie , what a slug is Hastings that he comes not To tell us whether they will come or no !

input: The sweating lord will come in good time.
target: And in good time here comes the sweating lord .

input: My lord, welcome to the world.
target: Welcome , my lord .

input: What will our mother do?
target: What , will our mother come ?

input: The queen your mother and your brother York have taken sanctuary, not me.
target: On what occasion God He knows , not I , The queen your mother and your brother York Have taken sanctuary .

input: The prince would have come with me to meet you, but he was not allowed by his mother to do so.
target: The tender prince Would fain have come with me to meet your Grace , But by his mother was perforce withheld .

input: I wouldn't be guilty of so deep a sin for all of this land.
target: Not for all this land Would I be guilty of so deep a sin .

input: You break not sanctuary in seizing him because of the grossness of this age.
target: Weigh it but with the grossness of this age , You break not sanctuary in seizing him .

input: In my opinion, this prince cannot have it because he neither claimed nor deserved it.
target: This prince hath neither claimed it nor deserved it And therefore , in mine opinion , can not have it .

input: I have not heard of sanctuary men or sanctuary children.
target: Oft have I heard of sanctuary men , But sanctuary children , ne'er till now .

input: Come on, Lord Hastings, will you join me for a ride?
target: My lord , you shall o'errule my mind for once. , Come on , Lord Hastings , will you go with me ?

input: My lord, I am going.
target: I go , my lord .

input: Good lords, make haste, you may be late.
target: Good lords , make all the speedy haste you may .

input: If our brother comes, where shall we stay till our coronation?
target: Say , uncle Gloucester , if our brother come , Where shall we sojourn till our coronation ?

input: Where it seems best to you, your royal self.
target: Where it seems best unto your royal self .

input: I don't like the Tower, my lord. Did Julius Caesar build that place?
target: I do not like the Tower , of any place. , Did Julius Caesar build that place , my lord ?

input: Since succeeding ages have re-edified, my gracious lord, he did start that place.
target: He did , my gracious lord , begin that place , Which , since , succeeding ages have re-edified .

input: He built it from age to age, so is it upon record or otherwise?
target: Is it upon record , or else reported Successively from age to age , he built it ?

input: My gracious lord, upon record.
target: Upon record , my gracious lord .

input: The truth should live from age to age, even if it wasn't registered, says my lord.
target: But say , my lord , it were not registered , Methinks the truth should live from age to age , As 'twere retailed to all posterity , Even to the general all-ending day .

input: What do you think about it, uncle?
target: What say you , uncle ?

input: Death doesn't make a conquest of this conqueror, he lives in fame, though not in life.
target: Death makes no conquest of this conqueror , For now he lives in fame , though not in life .

input: I hope George is packed with post- horse up to heaven so he can live to see the end.
target: He can not live , I hope , and must not die Till George be packed with post-horse up to heaven .

input: I'll get married to the youngest daughter of Warwick.
target: For then I'll marry Warwick's youngest daughter .

input: I didn't kill her husband and her father.
target: What though I killed her husband and her father ?

input: To become her husband and her father is the readiest way to make the wench amends, as for another secret close intent, I must marry her.
target: The readiest way to make the wench amends Is to become her husband and her father ; The which will I , not all so much for love As for another secret close intent By marrying her which I must reach unto .

input: I run before my horse to sell something.
target: But yet I run before my horse to market .

input: Clarence is still breathing and Edward is still in charge.
target: Clarence still breathes ; Edward still lives and reigns .

input: I need to count my gains when they are gone.
target: When they are gone , then must I count my gains .

input: My gracious lord, what are you talking about?
target: What , my gracious lord ?

input: How does our brother fare against Richard of York?
target: Richard of York , how fares our loving brother ?

input: I need to call you now, my dread lord.
target: Well , my dread lord , so must I call you now .

input: How do we fare against our cousin, Lord of York?
target: How fares our cousin , noble Lord of York ?

input: I would like to say thank you, gentle uncle.
target: I thank you , gentle uncle .

input: Idling weeds are fast in growth, said my lord.
target: O , my lord , You said that idle weeds are fast in growth .

input: The prince outgrew me, my brother.
target: The prince my brother hath outgrown me far .

input: My lord, he has, my lord.
target: He hath , my lord .

input: And therefore is he not doing anything?
target: And therefore is he idle ?

input: I must not say that, my cousin.
target: O , my fair cousin , I must not say so .

input: I don't know if he is more beholding to you than I am.
target: Then is he more beholding to you than I .

input: You have power in me as a kinsman, even though he may command me as his own.
target: He may command me as my sovereign , But you have power in me as in a kinsman .

input: I pray that you give me this dagger.
target: I pray you , uncle , give me this dagger .

input: My dagger is my little cousin.
target: My dagger , little cousin ?

input: With all of my heart.
target: With all my heart .

input: A brother and a beggar?
target: A beggar , brother ?

input: Being a toy, which is no grief to give, is what my kind uncle will give.
target: Of my kind uncle , that I know will give , And being but a toy , which is no grief to give .

input: I'll give my cousin a bigger gift than that.
target: A greater gift than that I'll give my cousin .

input: A gift of more magnitude?
target: A greater gift ?

input: That's the weapon to it.
target: O , that's the sword to it .

input: Were it light enough? Ay, gentle cousin.
target: Ay , gentle cousin , were it light enough .

input: I see that you will part but with light gifts.
target: O , then I see you will part but with light gifts .

input: In heavier things you will say a beggar.
target: In weightier things you'll say a beggar nay .

input: It is too heavy for your Grace to wear.
target: It is too heavy for your Grace to wear .

input: I weighed it lightly and wondered if it was heavier than I thought.
target: I weigh it lightly , were it heavier .

input: How do you do it?
target: How ?

input: Your Grace knows how to deal with your uncle.
target: Uncle , your Grace knows how to bear with him .

input: My brother mocks both you and me because he thinks you mean to not bear with me.
target: You mean , to bear me , not to bear with me. , Uncle , my brother mocks both you and me .

input: I will not sleep in quiet at the Tower.
target: I shall not sleep in quiet at the Tower .

input: What should you be afraid of?
target: Why , what should you fear ?

input: Clarence was an angry ghost and I wanted to Marry him.
target: Marry , my uncle Clarence ' angry ghost .

input: My grandam told me that he had been murdered there.
target: My grandam told me he was murdered there .

input: I don't think my uncles will be dead.
target: I fear no uncles dead .

input: I hope that none of them survive.
target: Nor none that live , I hope .

input: I hope they live, and I don't need to fear them.
target: An if they live , I hope I need not fear .

input: No question, no doubt.
target: No doubt , no doubt .

input: "Tis a parlous boy, bold, quick, ingenious, forward, capable."
target: O , 'tis a parlous boy , Bold , quick , ingenious , forward , capable .

input: He is the mother's child from the bottom to the top.
target: He is all the mother's , from the top to toe .

input: Let them rest, come hither, Catesby.
target: Well , let them rest. , Come hither , Catesby .

input: For his father's sake, he loves the prince so much that he won't be defeated against him.
target: He , for his father's sake , so loves the prince That he will not be won to aught against him .

input: Stanley, what do you think about it?
target: What think'st thou then of Stanley ?

input: Will he not do something?
target: Will not he ?

input: He will do everything as Hastings doth.
target: He will do all in all as Hastings doth .

input: As it were far off, sound Lord Hastings how he doth stand affected to our purpose, and summon him tomorrow to the Tower to sit about the coronation.
target: Well then , no more but this : go , gentle Catesby , And , as it were far off , sound thou Lord Hastings How he doth stand affected to our purpose And summon him tomorrow to the Tower To sit about the coronation .

input: Encourage him and show him all our reasons if we find him tractable to us.
target: If thou dost find him tractable to us , Encourage him and show him all our reasons .

input: Give us notice of his inclination if he be leaden, icy, cold, unwilling, and so break off the conversation.
target: If he be leaden , icy , cold , unwilling , Be thou so too , and so break off the talk , And give us notice of his inclination ; For we tomorrow hold divided councils , Wherein thyself shalt highly be employed .

input: I would like to convey my greetings to Lord William.
target: Commend me to Lord William .

input: Both of my good lords, with all the attention I can give them.
target: My good lords both , with all the heed I can .

input: Is it possible that we will hear from you, Catesby?
target: Shall we hear from you , Catesby , ere we sleep ?

input: My lord, you shall, you shall.
target: You shall , my lord .

input: At Crosby Place, you will find us both.
target: At Crosby Place , there shall you find us both .

input: Now, my lord, what should we do if we think Lord Hastings won't yield to our demands.
target: Now , my lord , what shall we do , if we perceive Lord Hastings will not yield to our complots ?

input: He should have chopped his head off.
target: Chop off his head .

input: Something we will figure out.
target: Something we will determine .

input: When I am king, I will claim the earldom of Hereford, and all the other places where my brother was.
target: And look when I am king , claim thou of me The earldom of Hereford , and all the moveables Whereof the king my brother was possessed .

input: At your Grace's hands, I will claim that promise.
target: I'll claim that promise at your Grace's hands .

input: Look for it to be yielded with all of the kindness.
target: And look to have it yielded with all kindness .

input: We might digest our complots in some form after that.
target: Come , let us sup betimes , that afterwards We may digest our complots in some form .

input: There is one from the Lord Stanley.
target: One from the Lord Stanley .

input: The stroke happened at four.
target: Upon the stroke of four .

input: Is it possible that my Lord Stanley can't sleep these nights?
target: Can not my Lord Stanley sleep these tedious nights ?

input: It appears to me that I have to say that.
target: So it appears by that I have to say .

input: He commends him to your noble self.
target: First , he commends him to your noble self .

input: What do you think about that?
target: What then ?

input: He dreamt that the boar had destroyed his helm, and that there were two council kept, which may make you and him to rue at the other council.
target: Then certifies your Lordship that this night He dreamt the boar had razed his helm Besides , he says there are two councils kept , And that may be determined at the one Which may make you and him to rue at th ' other .

input: His Honor and myself are at the one, and at the other is my good friend Catesby, where nothing can proceed that will touch us.
target: His Honor and myself are at the one , And at the other is my good friend Catesby , Where nothing can proceed that toucheth us Whereof I shall not have intelligence .

input: Tell him that his fears are not very serious.
target: Tell him his fears are shallow , without instance .

input: I wonder if he is so simple to trust the mock'ry of un quiet slumbers.
target: And for his dreams , I wonder he's so simple To trust the mock'ry of unquiet slumbers .

input: To make the chase where he did not mean no chase, and to incense the boar to follow us.
target: To fly the boar before the boar pursues Were to incense the boar to follow us And make pursuit where he did mean no chase .

input: Tomorrow is a good day for my noble lord.
target: Many good morrows to my noble lord .

input: Good tomorrow, Catesby.
target: Good morrow , Catesby .

input: You are stirring very early.
target: You are early stirring .

input: What news is happening in this state?
target: What news , what news in this our tott'ring state ?

input: It is a reeling world, my lord, and I believe will never stand upright, until Richard wears the garlands of the realm.
target: It is a reeling world indeed , my lord , And I believe will never stand upright Till Richard wear the garland of the realm .

input: How are you supposed to wear the garlands?
target: How "wear the garland" ?

input: Dost you mean the crown?
target: Dost thou mean the crown ?

input: Thank you, my good lord.
target: Ay , my good lord .

input: I'll have this crown cut from my shoulders before I can see it.
target: I'll have this crown of mine cut from my shoulders Before I'll see the crown so foul misplaced .

input: Is it possible that he aim at it?
target: But canst thou guess that he doth aim at it ?

input: He sent you this good news, that your enemies must die at Pomfret, because he hopes to find you forward.
target: Ay , on my life , and hopes to find you forward Upon his party for the gain thereof ; And thereupon he sends you this good news , That this same very day your enemies , The kindred of the queen , must die at Pomfret .

input: I am not a mourner for that news because they have been my adversaries.
target: Indeed , I am no mourner for that news , Because they have been still my adversaries .

input: God, keep your Lordship in your thoughts.
target: God keep your Lordship in that gracious mind .

input: I'll send some packing, but I won't think about it until I'm older.
target: Well , Catesby , ere a fortnight make me older I'll send some packing that yet think not on 't .

input: It's a vile thing to die, my gracious lord, when men are not prepared.
target: Tis a vile thing to die , my gracious lord , When men are unprepared and look not for it .

input: O monstrous, monstrous.
target: O monstrous , monstrous !

input: With some men that think themselves as safe as Richard and Buckingham, and so fall it out with them.
target: And so falls it out With Rivers , Vaughan , Grey ; and so 'twill do With some men else that think themselves as safe As thou and I , who , as thou know'st , are dear To princely Richard and to Buckingham .

input: The princes make a high account of you, I know they do, and I have been well deserved.
target: The princes both make high account of you , I know they do , and I have well deserved it .

input: Do you fear the pig and go without?
target: Fear you the boar , and go so unprovided ?

input: Tomorrow, my lord, good day.
target: My lord , good morrow .

input: I don't like these several councils, but you may say that, but I do not agree with you.
target: Good morrow , Catesby. , You may jest on , but , by the Holy Rood , I do not like these several councils , I .

input: My lord, I hold my life as dear as you do, and never in my days did I protest, Was it so precious to me as now?
target: My lord , I hold my life as dear as you do yours , And never in my days , I do protest , Was it so precious to me as 'tis now .

input: I would be so triumphant if I knew our state was secure.
target: Think you but that I know our state secure , I would be so triumphant as I am ?

input: I plead with God to help me, I prove a needless cowardice.
target: Pray God , I say , I prove a needless coward !

input: What should we do to get to the Tower?
target: What , shall we toward the Tower ?

input: The day is not done.
target: The day is spent .

input: Set down, set down your honorable load, if honor is shrouded in a hearse, whilst I regret the fall of Lancaster.
target: Set down , set down your honorable load , If honor may be shrouded in a hearse , Whilst I awhile obsequiously lament Th ' untimely fall of virtuous Lancaster .

input: My lord, what do you think about me?
target: Wot you what , my lord ?

input: The lords you talked about are no longer alive.
target: Today the lords you talked of are beheaded .

input: For their truth, they might better wear their heads than those that have accused them of wearing their hats.
target: They , for their truth , might better wear their heads Than some that have accused them wear their hats .

input: Come, my lord, let's go away.
target: But come , my lord , let's away .

input: Go on before then.
target: Go on before .

input: I'll talk with this person.
target: I'll talk with this good fellow .

input: How are you now, sirrah?
target: How now , sirrah !

input: What goes the world with thee?
target: How goes the world with thee ?

input: Please ask the better that you can, Lordship.
target: The better that your Lordship please to ask .

input: I tell the man that he is better with me now than when he met me last.
target: I tell thee , man , 'tis better with me now Than when thou met'st me last where now we meet .

input: This day those enemies are put to death, and I in better state than I was, I tell thee to keep it to thyself.
target: But now , I tell thee , keep it to thyself , This day those enemies are put to death , And I in better state than e'er I was .

input: To your honor's good content, hold it.
target: God hold it , to your Honor's good content !

input: It's time to drink that for me.
target: There , drink that for me .

input: I would like to thank your honor.
target: I thank your Honor .

input: I met you, my lord.
target: Well met , my lord .

input: I'm happy to see your honor.
target: I am glad to see your Honor .

input: I would like to thank Sir John, with all of my heart.
target: I thank thee , good Sir John , with all my heart .

input: I'm in debt to you for your last exercise.
target: I am in your debt for your last exercise .

input: Come the next sabbath, and I will be content with you.
target: Come the next sabbath , and I will content you .

input: Your Honor, your friends at Pomfret need the priest, but you don't have any work to do.
target: Your friends at Pomfret , they do need the priest ; Your Honor hath no shriving work in hand .

input: Good faith, and when I met this holy man, the men you talk about came into my mind.
target: Good faith , and when I met this holy man , The men you talk of came into my mind .

input: What are you going to do towards the Tower?
target: What , go you toward the Tower ?

input: I will come back before your lordship.
target: I shall return before your Lordship thence .

input: I will stay dinner there.
target: Nay , like enough , for I stay dinner there .

input: I will wait for your Lordship.
target: I'll wait upon your Lordship .

input: Dispatch was dispatched.
target: Dispatch .

input: The limits of your life are over.
target: The limit of your lives is out .

input: O Pomfret, Pomfret!
target: O Pomfret , Pomfret !

input: O bloody prison, Fatal and ominous to noble peers.
target: O thou bloody prison , Fatal and ominous to noble peers !

input: Margaret's curse isfall'n upon our heads, when she exclaimed on Hastings, you and I, for standing by when Richard stabbed her son.
target: Now Margaret's curse is fall'n upon our heads , When she exclaimed on Hastings , you , and I , For standing by when Richard stabbed her son .

input: Then she cursed the man.
target: Then cursed she Hastings .

input: Remember, God, To hear her prayer for them, as now for us.
target: O , remember , God , To hear her prayer for them , as now for us !

input: For my sister and her princely sons, please be satisfied, dear God, with our true blood, which must be split unjustifiably.
target: And for my sister and her princely sons , Be satisfied , dear God , with our true blood , Which , as thou know'st , unjustly must be spilt .

input: Make haste, make haste.
target: Make haste .

input: The hour of death is meaningless.
target: The hour of death is expiate .

input: Grey, come, come.
target: Come , Grey .

input: Come with me, Vaughan.
target: Come , Vaughan .

input: Let us all embrace each other.
target: Let us all embrace .

input: Speak in the name of the Almighty.
target: In God's name , speak .

input: The day is called the royal day.
target: When is the royal day ?

input: Is everything ready for the royal wedding?
target: Is all things ready for the royal time ?

input: It wants but does not want to be nominated.
target: It is , and wants but nomination .

input: Tomorrow, I will judge a happy day.
target: Tomorrow , then , I judge a happy day .

input: Who is aware of the Lord Protector's mind?
target: Who knows the Lord Protector's mind herein ?

input: The noble duke is most inward with someone.
target: Who is most inward with the noble duke ?

input: We think that your Grace should know his mind soon.
target: Your Grace , we think , should soonest know his mind .

input: We know each other's faces, for our hearts, He knows no more of my face than you do.
target: We know each other's faces ; for our hearts , He knows no more of mine than I of yours , Or I of his , my lord , than you of mine. , Lord Hastings , you and he are near in love .

input: I would like to thank him for his Grace.
target: I thank his Grace .

input: I know that he adores me.
target: I know he loves me well .

input: I haven't spoken to him or delivered his gracious pleasure for his purpose in the coronation.
target: But for his purpose in the coronation , I have not sounded him , nor he delivered His gracious pleasure any way therein .

input: I'll give my voice in the duke's behalf, which I assume he'll take in gentle part, but you may name the time.
target: But you , my honorable lords , may name the time , And in the duke's behalf I'll give my voice , Which I presume he'll take in gentle part .

input: The duke comes here in happy times.
target: In happy time here comes the duke himself .

input: Good tomorrow, my noble lords and cousins.
target: My noble lords and cousins all , good morrow .

input: William Lord Hastings had said your voice for crowning the king if you had not come upon your cue.
target: Had you not come upon your cue , my lord , William Lord Hastings had pronounced your part , I mean your voice for crowning of the king .

input: No man could be bolder than my lord Hastings.
target: Than my Lord Hastings no man might be bolder .

input: A word with you from your cousin of Buckingham.
target: Cousin of Buckingham , a word with you .

input: I will go with you.
target: I'll go with you .

input: This day of triumph has not yet been set down.
target: We have not yet set down this day of triumph .

input: The duke of Gloucester is located somewhere.
target: Where is my lord the duke of Gloucester ?

input: These strawberries have been sent for by me.
target: I have sent for these strawberries .

input: This morning, his grace looks smooth and cheerful.
target: His grace looks cheerfully and smooth this morning .

input: He bids good morrow with such spirit that there's some conceit or other that likes him.
target: There's some conceit or other likes him well When that he bids good morrow with such spirit .

input: I think there's never a man in Christendom who hides his love or hate better than he does.
target: I think there's never a man in Christendom Can lesser hide his love or hate than he , For by his face straight shall you know his heart .

input: I am praying that he be not.
target: I pray God he be not , I say .

input: You should be the witness of their evil.
target: Then be your eyes the witness of their evil .

input: My noble lord, if they have done this deed,
target: If they have done this deed , my noble lord , If ?

input: Talk'st to me of "ifs" if you want to protect this damned strumpet.
target: Thou protector of this damned strumpet , Talk'st thou to me of "ifs" ?

input: Thou art a traitor and off with his head.
target: Thou art a traitor , Off with his head .

input: It's terrible for England.
target: Woe , woe for England !

input: Stanley had a dream that the boar would raze his helm and he did not like it.
target: Stanley did dream the boar did raze his helm , And I did scorn it and disdain to fly .

input: Three times today my foot-cloth horse stumbled, and started when he looked upon the Tower.
target: Three times today my foot-cloth horse did stumble , And started when he looked upon the Tower , As loath to bear me to the slaughterhouse .

input: I need the priest that spake to me now.
target: O , now I need the priest that spake to me !

input: I told the pursuivant how my enemies were butchered at Pomfret and how I myself was secure in grace and favor.
target: I now repent I told the pursuivant , As too triumphing , how mine enemies Today at Pomfret bloodily were butchered , And I myself secure in grace and favor .

input: Margaret, now your curse is lighted on poor Hastings' wretched head.
target: O Margaret , Margaret , now thy heavy curse Is lighted on poor Hastings ' wretched head .

input: A short shrift is what you should make.
target: Make a short shrift .

input: He wants you to see your head.
target: He longs to see your head .

input: The grace of God is more important to us than the momentary grace of mortal men.
target: O momentary grace of mortal men , Which we more hunt for than the grace of God !

input: Who builds his hopes in air of your good looks lives like a drunken sailor on a mast and ready with every nod to tumble down into the fatal bowels of the deep.
target: Who builds his hopes in air of your good looks Lives like a drunken sailor on a mast , Ready with every nod to tumble down Into the fatal bowels of the deep .

input: dispatch come and dispatch come and dispatch come and dispatch come and dispatch come and dispatch come and dispatch come and dispatch come and dispatch come and dispatch come and dispatch come and dispatch come and dispatch come and dispatch come and dispatch come and dispatch come and dispatch come and dispatch come and dispatch come and dispatch
target: Come , come , dispatch .

input: It is bootless to say something.
target: Tis bootless to exclaim .

input: Richard, O bloody Richard!
target: O bloody Richard !

input: I prophesy the fearfull'st time to thee, that ever wretched age has looked upon England.
target: Miserable England , I prophesy the fearfull'st time to thee That ever wretched age hath looked upon. , Come , lead me to the block .

input: Don't let him get to your head.
target: Bear him my head .

input: They smile at me and say that I will be dead soon.
target: They smile at me that shortly shall be dead .

input: Both of them are ready in their offices, at any time, to grace my stratagems.
target: Ghastly looks Are at my service , like enforced smiles , And both are ready in their offices , At any time to grace my stratagems .

input: But what about Catesby?
target: But what , is Catesby gone ?

input: O'er look at the walls, Catesby.
target: Catesby , o'erlook the walls .

input: If ever he have a wife, let her be miserable by the death of him. I am made by my poor lord and thee.
target: If ever he have wife , let her be made More miserable by the death of him Than I am made by my poor lord and thee. , Come now towards Chertsey with your holy load , Taken from Paul's to be interred there .

input: This fiend is conjured up by a black magician to stop charitable work.
target: What black magician conjures up this fiend To stop devoted charitable deeds ?

input: Look back, Lord Mayor, the reason we have sent.
target: Lord Mayor , the reason we have sent , Look back !

input: Defending thee!
target: Defend thee !

input: Here are people who are enemies.
target: Here are enemies .

input: Our innocence is defended by God and our innocence is guarded by him.
target: God and our innocence defend and guard us !

input: You should be patient.
target: Be patient .

input: They are friends with Ratcliffe and Lovell.
target: They are friends , Ratcliffe and Lovell .

input: The head of that ignoble traitor is The dangerous and unsuspected Hastings.
target: Here is the head of that ignoble traitor , The dangerous and unsuspected Hastings .

input: I must weep because I loved the man so much.
target: So dear I loved the man that I must weep .

input: He lived from all attainder of suspects, because he was so smooth he daubed his vice with show of virtue, and his apparent open guilt was omitted.
target: So smooth he daubed his vice with show of virtue That , his apparent open guilt omitted , I mean his conversation with Shore's wife , He lived from all attainder of suspects .

input: Did he have done that?
target: Had he done so ?

input: What do you think about us being Turks or infidels?
target: What , think you we are Turks or infidels ?

input: I was always looking for better at his hands after he fell in with Mistress Shore.
target: I never looked for better at his hands After he once fell in with Mistress Shore .

input: My good lord, your Graces' words will serve as well as I had seen and heard him speak, right noble princes both, but I'll give our duteous citizens all your just proceedings in this case.
target: But , my good lord , your Graces ' words shall serve As well as I had seen and heard him speak ; And do not doubt , right noble princes both , But I'll acquaint our duteous citizens With all your just proceedings in this case .

input: We wish that your Lordship avoided the censures of the carping world.
target: And to that end we wished your Lordship here T ' avoid the censures of the carping world .

input: He lusted to make his prey even where his raging eye or savage heart could not be controlled.
target: Moreover , urge his hateful luxury And bestial appetite in change of lust , Which stretched to their servants , daughters , wives , Even where his raging eye or savage heart , Without control , lusted to make his prey .

input: Tell them when my mother went with Edward, my princely father had wars in France, and Found.
target: Nay , for a need , thus far come near my person : Tell them when that my mother went with child Of that insatiate Edward , noble York My princely father then had wars in France , And , by true computation of the time , Found that the issue was not his begot , Which well appeared in his lineaments , Being nothing like the noble duke my father .

input: As my lord, you know that my mother lives, so don't touch this too much.
target: Yet touch this sparingly , as 'twere far off , Because , my lord , you know my mother lives .

input: And so, my lord, adieu.
target: And so , my lord , adieu .

input: If you thrive well, bring them to Baynard's Castle, where you will find me accompanied by your reverend fathers and well-learned bishops.
target: If you thrive well , bring them to Baynard's Castle , Where you shall find me well accompanied With reverend fathers and well-learned bishops .

input: I look for the news that the Guildhall gives at three or four o'clock.
target: I go ; and towards three or four o'clock Look for the news that the Guildhall affords .

input: Go, Lovell, with all your strength to Doctor Shaw.
target: Go , Lovell , with all speed to Doctor Shaw .

input: I need to get the brats of Clarence out of sight, and to give order that no manner of person can do.
target: Now will I go to take some privy order To draw the brats of Clarence out of sight , And to give order that no manner of person Have any time recourse unto the princes .

input: Here's a good world for a while.
target: Here's a good world the while .

input: Who is gross that can not see this device?
target: Who is so gross That can not see this palpable device ?

input: Bad is the world, and all will come to naught when such ill dealing is seen in thought.
target: Bad is the world , and all will come to naught When such ill dealing must be seen in thought .

input: The citizens are mum, by the holy mother of our Lord, say not a word.
target: Now , by the holy mother of our Lord , The citizens are mum , say not a word .

input: Is it possible that you were touched by Edward's children?
target: Touched you the bastardy of Edward's children ?

input: No, that's not true.
target: No .

input: The people were not used to being talked to by the recorder.
target: His answer was , the people were not used To be spoke to but by the recorder .

input: Would they not say something?
target: Would not they speak ?

input: Will the mayor and his brethren not show up?
target: Will not the mayor then and his brethren come ?

input: The mayor is at his office.
target: The mayor is here at hand .

input: I'll make a holy descant if you stand between two churchmen and have a prayer book in your hands.
target: And look you get a prayer book in your hand And stand between two churchmen , good my lord , For on that ground I'll make a holy descant .

input: To our requests, be not easy to win.
target: And be not easily won to our requests .

input: I am going.
target: I go .

input: I can say "nay" to thee for myself, but we bring it to a happy issue.
target: An if you plead as well for them As I can say "nay" to thee for myself , No doubt we bring it to a happy issue .

input: Go, go, go up to the leads.
target: Go , go , up to the leads .

input: The Lord Mayor is making noise.
target: The Lord Mayor knocks .

input: My lord, welcome to the world.
target: Welcome , my lord .

input: I think the duke won't be speaking withal.
target: I think the duke will not be spoke withal .

input: What does your lord say to my request, Catesby?
target: Now , Catesby , what says your lord to my request ?

input: He wants to visit him tomorrow or the next day, my noble lord.
target: He doth entreat your Grace , my noble lord , To visit him tomorrow or next day .

input: Return to the duke, good Catesby.
target: Return , good Catesby , to the gracious duke .

input: Tell him myself, the mayor, and the aldermen, No less import than our general good, in deep designs, and matters of great moment, and come to have some conference with his grace.
target: Tell him myself , the mayor , and aldermen , No less importing than our general good , In deep designs , and matters of great moment Are come to have some conference with his grace .

input: I will signify so much to him straight.
target: I'll signify so much unto him straight .

input: Ah, my lord, this prince is not Edward.
target: Ah , ha , my lord , this prince is not an Edward !

input: He is meditating with two deep divines, but not sleeping, and he is not laughing on a lewd love bed.
target: He is not lolling on a lewd love bed , But on his knees at meditation ; Not dallying with a brace of courtesans , But meditating with two deep divines ; Not sleeping , to engross his idle body , But praying , to enrich his watchful soul .

input: Would England be happy if this prince took on his own sovereignty?
target: Happy were England would this virtuous prince Take on his grave the sovereignty thereof .

input: I am afraid that we will not win him to it.
target: But sure I fear we shall not win him to it .

input: Marry, God defend his grace should say no.
target: Marry , God defend his grace should say us nay !

input: I fear he will do that.
target: I fear he will .

input: This is where Catesby arrives again.
target: Here Catesby comes again .

input: What does his grace say, Catesby?
target: Now , Catesby , what says his grace ?

input: He wonders what the end of the troops of citizens that have been assembled to come to him will be.
target: He wonders to what end you have assembled Such troops of citizens to come to him , His grace not being warned thereof before .

input: He is afraid, my lord, you mean no good to him.
target: He fears , my lord , you mean no good to him .

input: I should suspect that I mean no good to him because I am my noble cousin.
target: Sorry I am my noble cousin should Suspect me that I mean no good to him .

input: When religious men are at their beads, it's much to draw them thence and so sweet.
target: When holy and devout religious men Are at their beads , 'tis much to draw them thence , So sweet is zealous contemplation .

input: There are two clergymen who see where his Grace stands.
target: See where his Grace stands , 'tween two clergymen .

input: There is no need for an apology from my lord.
target: My lord , there needs no such apology .

input: I plead with your Grace to pardon me, who is in the service of my God, and to allow my friends to come and go as they please.
target: I do beseech your Grace pardon me , Who , earnest in the service of my God , Deferred the visitation of my friends .

input: I think I have done something that seems disgracious in the city's eye, and that you come to reprehend my ignorance.
target: I do suspect I have done some offense That seems disgracious in the city's eye , And that you come to reprehend my ignorance .

input: You have, my lord, you have.
target: You have , my lord .

input: For charity, be a sweet saint, but be not so strict.
target: Sweet saint , for charity , be not so curst .

input: This pattern of butcheries is if you want to view the heinous acts of thyself.
target: If thou delight to view thy heinous deeds , Behold this pattern of thy butcheries .

input: See dead Henry's wounds, open their congealed mouths and bleed afresh!
target: O , gentlemen , see , see dead Henry's wounds Open their congealed mouths and bleed afresh ! , Blush , blush , thou lump of foul deformity , For 'tis thy presence that exhales this blood From cold and empty veins where no blood dwells .

input: This blood drink'st revenge his death, O earth.
target: O earth , which this blood drink'st revenge his death !

input: Either heaven with lightning strike the murderer dead, or earth gape open wide and eat him quick, as he was butchered by his own arm.
target: Either heaven with lightning strike the murderer dead , Or earth gape open wide and eat him quick , As thou dost swallow up this good king's blood , Which his hell-governed arm hath butchered !

input: If you don't reply, you might think that you gave up the golden yoke of sovereignty, which you would here impose on me.
target: If not to answer , you might haply think Tongue-tied ambition , not replying , yielded To bear the golden yoke of sovereignty , Which fondly you would here impose on me .

input: If all obstacles were cut away, my path was even to the crown, as the ripe revenue and due of birth, yet so much is my poverty of spirit, so mighty and so many my defects, that I would rather hide myself from my greatness.
target: First , if all obstacles were cut away And that my path were even to the crown As the ripe revenue and due of birth , Yet so much is my poverty of spirit , So mighty and so many my defects , That I would rather hide me from my greatness , Being a bark to brook no mighty sea , Than in my greatness covet to be hid And in the vapor of my glory smothered .

input: I need to help you, but there is no need for me, and much I need to help you.
target: But , God be thanked , there is no need of me , And much I need to help you , were there need .

input: The royal tree gave us royal fruit, which mellowed by the stealing hours of time, and will become the seat of majesty.
target: The royal tree hath left us royal fruit , Which , mellowed by the stealing hours of time , Will well become the seat of majesty , And make , no doubt , us happy by his reign .

input: The right and fortune of his happy stars, which God defend that I should wring from him, were laid on him by me.
target: On him I lay what you would lay on me , The right and fortune of his happy stars , Which God defend that I should wring from him .

input: Your mother lives a witness to that vow, and afterwards by substitute betrothed To Bona, sister to the king of France.
target: For first was he contract to Lady Lucy , Your mother lives a witness to that vow , And afterward by substitute betrothed To Bona , sister to the king of France .

input: These both put off, a poor petitioner, a care-crazed mother to a number of sons, and a beauty-waning and distressed widow, Even in the afternoon of her best days, Seduced the pitch.
target: These both put off , a poor petitioner , A care-crazed mother to a many sons , A beauty-waning and distressed widow , Even in the afternoon of her best days , Made prize and purchase of his wanton eye , Seduced the pitch and height of his degree To base declension and loathed bigamy .

input: This proffered love, mighty lord, you must refuse not.
target: Refuse not , mighty lord , this proffered love .

input: O, make them happy.
target: O , make them joyful .

input: They should be granted their lawful suit.
target: Grant their lawful suit .

input: Why would you care so much about me?
target: Alas , why would you heap this care on me ?

input: I am not fit to be a state and majesty.
target: I am unfit for state and majesty .

input: I plead with you to take it not amiss, I can not and I will not yield to you.
target: I do beseech you , take it not amiss ; I can not , nor I will not , yield to you .

input: Zounds, I'll stop asking.
target: Zounds , I'll entreat no more .

input: Do not swear, my lord of Buckingham!
target: O , do not swear , my lord of Buckingham !

input: All the land will feel bad if you deny them.
target: If you deny them , all the land will rue it .

input: Is it possible that you will enforce me to a world of cares?
target: Will you enforce me to a world of cares ?

input: They should be called again.
target: Call them again .

input: I am not made of stones, but penetrable to your kind entreaties, which is against my conscience and my soul.
target: I am not made of stones , But penetrable to your kind entreaties , Albeit against my conscience and my soul .

input: Thank you God for your Grace!
target: God bless your Grace !

input: We will say it, and we see it.
target: We see it and will say it .

input: You will say the truth, but not the truth.
target: In saying so , you shall but say the truth .

input: I salute you with the title of "Richard, England's worthy king".
target: Then I salute you with this royal title : Long live Richard , England's worthy king !

input: Thank you, Amen.
target: Amen .

input: Will it make you happy to be crowned tomorrow?
target: Tomorrow will it please you to be crowned ?

input: Since you will have it, even when you please.
target: Even when you please , since you will have it so .

input: Who comes here to meet us?
target: Who meets us here ?

input: My niece Plantagenet was led in the hand of her kind aunt of Gloucester.
target: My niece Plantagenet Led in the hand of her kind aunt of Gloucester ?

input: For my life, she is going to the Tower to greet the prince.
target: Now , for my life , she's wandering to the Tower , On pure heart's love , to greet the tender prince. , Daughter , well met .

input: Is it possible that she is away?
target: Whither away ?

input: To gratulate the gentle princes there, and no farther than the Tower, as I guess.
target: No farther than the Tower , and , as I guess , Upon the like devotion as yourselves , To gratulate the gentle princes there .

input: Thanks sister, you are a good sister.
target: Kind sister , thanks .

input: We will enter all together.
target: We'll enter all together .

input: In good time, the lieutenant comes and prays for the prince and my young son.
target: And in good time here the lieutenant comes. , Master Lieutenant , pray you , by your leave , How doth the prince and my young son of York ?

input: Thank you very much, dear madam.
target: Right well , dear madam .

input: I may not suffer you to visit them if you are patient.
target: By your patience , I may not suffer you to visit them .

input: The king charged in the opposite direction.
target: The king hath strictly charged the contrary .

input: What is the name of the king?
target: The king ?

input: Who's that person?
target: Who's that ?

input: The Lord Protector is what I am referring to.
target: I mean , the Lord Protector .

input: He is protected from that title by the Lord.
target: The Lord protect him from that kingly title !

input: I wonder if he set bounds between their love and me.
target: Hath he set bounds between their love and me ?

input: I am their mother, too.
target: I am their mother .

input: Who will prevent me from them?
target: Who shall bar me from them ?

input: I am the mother of their father.
target: I am their father's mother .

input: I will see them when I can.
target: I will see them .

input: In love with their mother, their aunt I am in law.
target: Their aunt I am in law , in love their mother .

input: They should bring me to their sights.
target: Then bring me to their sights .

input: I will bear the blame and take the office from thee on my own.
target: I'll bear thy blame And take thy office from thee , on my peril .

input: No, madam, no.
target: No , madam , no .

input: I might not leave it that way.
target: I may not leave it so .

input: I am bound by an oath and therefore pardon myself.
target: I am bound by oath , and therefore pardon me .

input: I'll salute your Grace of York as mother and reverend looker on, of two fair queens, if I meet you one hour later.
target: Let me but meet you ladies one hour hence , And I'll salute your Grace of York as mother And reverend looker-on , of two fair queens .

input: Ah, cut my lace asunder, that my heart may have some scope to beat, or else, I will be so sad.
target: Ah , cut my lace asunder , That my pent heart may have some scope to beat , Or else I swoon with this dead-killing news !

input: The news is unpleasing.
target: O , unpleasing news !

input: The mother's name is frightening to children.
target: Thy mother's name is ominous to children .

input: You will have letters from me to my son in order to meet you on the way.
target: You shall have letters from me to my son In your behalf , to meet you on the way .

input: Don't be late because of a delay.
target: Be not ta'en tardy by unwise delay .

input: It was an ill-dispersing wind of misery.
target: O ill-dispersing wind of misery !

input: I will go if I don't want to.
target: And I in all unwillingness will go .

input: The golden metal that must round my brow would be red-hot steel to sear me to the brains.
target: O , would to God that the inclusive verge Of golden metal that must round my brow Were red-hot steel to sear me to the brains !

input: To feed my humor, wish them good fortune.
target: To feed my humor , wish thyself no harm .

input: No, that's not true.
target: No ?

input: Why do you think so?
target: Why ?

input: Adieu to the poor heart.
target: Poor heart , adieu .

input: I pity the person who is complaining.
target: I pity thy complaining .

input: I mourn for yours from my soul, no more than that.
target: No more than from my soul I mourn for yours .

input: I farewell, you wretched welcomer of glory.
target: Farewell , thou woeful welcomer of glory .

input: For tender princes, use my babies well, old ragged nurse.
target: Rude ragged nurse , old sullen playfellow For tender princes , use my babies well .

input: Your stones were bid farewell by foolish sorrows.
target: So foolish sorrows bids your stones farewell .

input: Lady, there are no rules of charity, which means good for bad and blessings for curses.
target: Lady , you know no rules of charity , Which renders good for bad , blessings for curses .

input: The law of God or man is not the villain.
target: Villain , thou know'st not law of God nor man .

input: There is no beast so fierce that knows some kind of pity.
target: No beast so fierce but knows some touch of pity .

input: I am no beast because I do not know any.
target: But I know none , and therefore am no beast .

input: When angels are angry, it's more wonderful.
target: More wonderful , when angels are so angry .

input: Vouchsafe, divine perfection of a woman, Of these supposed crimes to give me leave by circumstance but to acquit myself.
target: Vouchsafe , divine perfection of a woman , Of these supposed crimes to give me leave By circumstance but to acquit myself .

input: To give me leave by circumstance to curse my cursed self, is one of the known evils.
target: Vouchsafe , defused infection of a man , Of these known evils but to give me leave By circumstance to curse thy cursed self .

input: Let me have some patient leisure to excuse myself because I am Fairer than tongue.
target: Fairer than tongue can name thee , let me have Some patient leisure to excuse myself .

input: Fouler than heart can think of no excuse but to hang themselves.
target: Fouler than heart can think thee , thou canst make No excuse current but to hang thyself .

input: I should accuse myself of being so depressed.
target: By such despair I should accuse myself .

input: I am grateful to my gracious monarch.
target: My gracious sovereign .

input: Give me something to hold on to.
target: Give me thy hand .

input: By my advice and assistance is King Richard seated.
target: Thus high , by thy advice And thy assistance is King Richard seated .

input: Will we wear these glories for a day, or will they last for a long time?
target: But shall we wear these glories for a day , Or shall they last and we rejoice in them ?

input: Allow them to last forever, and still live they.
target: Still live they , and forever let them last .

input: Buckingham, do I try to get you to be current gold?
target: Ah , Buckingham , now do I play the touch , To try if thou be current gold indeed .

input: Think about what I would say now that Edward is dead.
target: Young Edward lives ; think now what I would speak .

input: Say on to my loving lord.
target: Say on , my loving lord .

input: I think it's a good thing!
target: Ha !

input: Edward lives, but he is so.
target: Tis so , but Edward lives .

input: It is true, noble prince.
target: True , noble prince .

input: Edward should live as a "true noble prince"!
target: O bitter consequence That Edward still should live "true noble prince" !

input: It isn't going to be so dull.
target: Cousin , thou wast not wont to be so dull .

input: Is it possible that I will be plain.
target: Shall I be plain ?

input: What do you think about it now?
target: What sayest thou now ?

input: Your Grace may be able to fulfill your desires.
target: Your Grace may do your pleasure .

input: Tut, tut, Thou art all ice ; Thou kindness is frozen.
target: Tut , tut , thou art all ice ; thy kindness freezes .

input: Have I given my consent that they will die?
target: Say , have I thy consent that they shall die ?

input: Give me some time to think, dear lord, before I say anything.
target: Give me some little breath , some pause , dear lord , Before I positively speak in this .

input: I will resolve you in the near future.
target: I will resolve you herein presently .

input: The boys were unrespective.
target: And unrespective boys .

input: Don't you know that corrupting gold will bring about a close exploit of death?
target: Know'st thou not any whom corrupting gold Will tempt unto a close exploit of death ?

input: What is his name, what is it?
target: What is his name ?

input: My lord, his name is  Tyrrel.
target: His name , my lord , is Tyrrel .

input: I know the man a little bit.
target: I partly know the man .

input: Go, call him hither, boy, no more will he be the neighbor to my counsels Hath he has held out with me for so long, tired, and stopped now for breath.
target: Go , call him hither , boy No more shall be the neighbor to my counsels Hath he so long held out with me , untired , And stops he now for breath ?

input: Well, be it so.
target: Well , be it so .

input: Lord Stanley, what is the news right now?
target: How now , Lord Stanley , what's the news ?

input: I hear that my long lord, the marquess Dorset, is fleeing to the parts where he lives.
target: Know , my long lord , The marquess Dorset , as I hear , is fled To Richmond , in the parts where he abides .

input: You should come hither, Catesby.
target: Come hither , Catesby .

input: There is a rumor that my wife is very sick.
target: Rumor it abroad That Anne my wife is very grievous sick .

input: I will marry Clarence's daughter straight away if you can find a mean poor gentleman.
target: Inquire me out some mean poor gentleman , Whom I will marry straight to Clarence ' daughter .

input: Look at how he dreams!
target: Look how thou dream'st !

input: Give out that Anne is sick and wants to die, I say again.
target: I say again , give out That Anne my queen is sick and like to die .

input: Is the name Tyrrel true?
target: Is thy name Tyrrel ?

input: James Tyrrel was your most obedient subject.
target: James Tyrrel , and your most obedient subject .

input: Is it true that art is indeed indeed?
target: Art thou indeed ?

input: Is it true that you want to kill a friend of mine?
target: Dar'st thou resolve to kill a friend of mine ?

input: Why is it that you have it?
target: Why then , thou hast it .

input: Two deep enemies, Foes to my rest and my sweet sleep's disturbers, are they that I would have thee deal with?
target: Two deep enemies , Foes to my rest , and my sweet sleep's disturbers , Are they that I would have thee deal upon .

input: Those people in the Tower are called Tyrrel.
target: Tyrrel , I mean those bastards in the Tower .

input: I'll rid you of the fear of them when I have open means to come to them.
target: Let me have open means to come to them , And soon I'll rid you from the fear of them .

input: Thou sing the sweetest music.
target: Thou sing'st sweet music .

input: Hark, come hither,  TYRREL.
target: Hark , come hither , Tyrrel .

input: Go with this token.
target: Go , by this token .

input: Rise, and lend the other person's ear.
target: Rise , and lend thine ear .

input: There is nothing left but that.
target: There is no more but so .

input: If it is done, I will love thee and prefer thee for it.
target: Say it is done , And I will love thee and prefer thee for it .

input: I will dispatch it in a timely manner.
target: I will dispatch it straight .

input: I have thought about the late request that you made to me.
target: My lord , I have considered in my mind The late request that you did sound me in .

input: Let that rest, well.
target: Well , let that rest .

input: The person fled to the other side of the country.
target: Dorset is fled to Richmond .

input: I am aware of the news, my lord.
target: I hear the news , my lord .

input: He is your wife's son, Stanley.
target: Stanley , he is your wife's son .

input: Well, look at it.
target: Well , look unto it .

input: My lord, I claim the gift, my due by promise, for which your honor and your faith is taken away, and the earldom of Hereford and the movables which you promised I would possess.
target: My lord , I claim the gift , my due by promise , For which your honor and your faith is pawned , Th ' earldom of Hereford and the movables Which you promised I shall possess .

input: Stanley, look to your spouse.
target: Stanley , look to your wife .

input: You will answer the letters if she conveys them toRichmond.
target: If she convey Letters to Richmond , you shall answer it .

input: What is your response to my request?
target: What says your Highness to my just request ?

input: I remember Henry the Sixth prophesying thatRichmond should be king when he was a little peevish boy.
target: I do remember me , Henry the Sixth Did prophesy that Richmond should be king , When Richmond was a little peevish boy .

input: I was told by the prophet that I should kill him, but I don't know if he could have done that at that time.
target: A king , perhaps , My lord , How chance the prophet could not at that time Have told me , I being by , that I should kill him ?

input: My lord, your promise for the earldom, Richmond!
target: My lord , your promise for the earldom , Richmond !

input: The mayor at the time showed me the castle and called it Rougemont, because a bard of Ireland told me I should not live long after I sawRichmond.
target: When last I was at Exeter , The mayor in courtesy showed me the castle And called it Rougemont , at which name I started , Because a bard of Ireland told me once I should not live long after I saw Richmond .

input: What's the time, my lord?
target: My Lord , Ay , what's o'clock ?

input: I am bold to put your Grace in mind of what you promised me.
target: I am thus bold to put your Grace in mind Of what you promised me .

input: Well, but what is the time?
target: Well , but what's o'clock ?

input: The stroke occurred at ten.
target: Upon the stroke of ten .

input: Let it strike, that's all.
target: Well , let it strike .

input: Why didn't you let it strike?
target: Why let it strike ?

input: Because that is like a jack, I keep'st the stroke and the meditation.
target: Because that , like a jack , thou keep'st the stroke Betwixt thy begging and my meditation .

input: I am not in the giving vein today.
target: I am not in the giving vein today .

input: I want to know whether you will or not.
target: Why then , resolve me whether you will or no .

input: I am not in the vein, I troublest you.
target: Thou troublest me ; I am not in the vein .

input: Is it therefore?
target: And is it thus ?

input: He should be paid for his deep service with such contempt.
target: Repays he my deep service With such deep contempt ?

input: Is it possible that he was made king for this?
target: Made I him king for this ?

input: Let me think about Hastings and be gone to Brecknock, while my head is throbbing.
target: O , let me think on Hastings and be gone To Brecknock , while my fearful head is on !

input: This land was guilty of the most arch deed of piteous massacre.
target: The tyrannous and bloody act is done , The most arch deed of piteous massacre That ever yet this land was guilty of .

input: Dighton and Forrest were like two children in their deaths, they were bloodthirsty and melted with mild compassion, but I suborned them to do this piece of ruthless butchery.
target: Dighton and Forrest , whom I did suborn To do this piece of ruthless butchery , Albeit they were fleshed villains , bloody dogs , Melted with tenderness and mild compassion , Wept like two children in their deaths ' sad story .

input: Their lips were filled with four red roses and they kissed each other.
target: Their lips were four red roses on a stalk , And in their summer beauty kissed each other .

input: Is it true that I am happy in the news.
target: Kind Tyrrel , am I happy in thy news ?

input: If you have done the thing you were given, then be happy, for it is done.
target: If to have done the thing you gave in charge Beget your happiness , be happy then , For it is done .

input: Is it possible that they saw them dead?
target: But did'st thou see them dead ?

input: My lord, I did, too.
target: I did , my lord .

input: Is it buried, gentle Tyrrel?
target: And buried , gentle Tyrrel ?

input: I don't know where to say the truth, because the tower's chaplain buried them.
target: The chaplain of the Tower hath buried them , But where , to say the truth , I do not know .

input: When shalt you tell the process of their death,,,,,,,,,, come to me,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
target: Come to me , Tyrrel , soon at after-supper , When thou shalt tell the process of their death .

input: I want to be inheritor of the desire of the person.
target: Meantime , but think how I may do thee good , And be inheritor of thy desire .

input: Until then, farewell till then.
target: Farewell till then .

input: I will take my leave.
target: I humbly take my leave .

input: Anne my wife bid this world goodnight as the sons of Edward slept in Abraham's bosom, the son of Clarence have I pent up close, his daughter meanly have I matched in marriage, and the son of Edward sleep in Abraham's bosom.
target: The son of Clarence have I pent up close , His daughter meanly have I matched in marriage , The sons of Edward sleep in Abraham's bosom , And Anne my wife hath bid this world goodnight .

input: By that knot looks proudly on the crown, my brother's daughter, and by that I am a jolly thriving wooer.
target: Now , for I know the Breton Richmond aims At young Elizabeth , my brother's daughter , And by that knot looks proudly on the crown , To her go I , a jolly thriving wooer .

input: My lord, my lord.
target: My lord !

input: Good or bad news, that is what it is.
target: Good or bad news , that thou com'st in so bluntly ?

input: My lord, there is bad news.
target: Bad news , my lord .

input: Morton fled to Buckingham and was supported by the Welshmen and still his power increased.
target: Morton is fled to Richmond , And Buckingham , backed with the hardy Welshmen , Is in the field , and still his power increaseth .

input: Buckingham's strength and rash-levied strength troubles me more near Ely.
target: Ely with Richmond troubles me more near Than Buckingham and his rash-levied strength .

input: Say that I did not slew them.
target: Say that I slew them not .

input: Say that they were not killed.
target: Then say they were not slain .

input: They are dead, and devilish slaves, by thee.
target: But dead they are , and devilish slave , by thee .

input: I did not murder your husband.
target: I did not kill your husband .

input: Why is he still alive?
target: Why then , he is alive .

input: Thou liest in the foul throat.
target: In thy foul throat thou liest .

input: Queen Margaret saw that the man was smoking in his blood, and that he once did bend against her breast.
target: Queen Margaret saw Thy murd'rous falchion smoking in his blood , The which thou once didst bend against her breast , But that thy brothers beat aside the point .

input: Their guilt was upon my guiltless shoulders because I was provoked by her tongue.
target: I was provoked by her sland'rous tongue , That laid their guilt upon my guiltless shoulders .

input: Thou was provoked by his bloody mind, that never dream'st on aught but butcheries.
target: Thou wast provoked by thy bloody mind , That never dream'st on aught but butcheries .

input: Is it possible that you didn't kill this king.
target: Didst thou not kill this king ?

input: I am willing to give you the benefit of the doubt.
target: I grant you .

input: Is it possible to grant me, hedgehog?
target: Dost grant me , hedgehog ?

input: Thou may be damned for that wicked deed, then, God, grant me as well.
target: Then , God grant me too Thou mayst be damned for that wicked deed .

input: He was gentle, mild, and righteous.
target: O , he was gentle , mild , and virtuous .

input: The best thing for the King of heaven is that he is free.
target: The better for the King of heaven that hath him .

input: He is in a place where he will never be seen.
target: He is in heaven , where thou shalt never come .

input: Let him say thank you, for he was better suited for that place than the earth was.
target: Let him thank me , that holp to send him thither , For he was fitter for that place than earth .

input: I have been here in these confines to watch the waning of my enemies.
target: Here in these confines slyly have I lurked To watch the waning of mine enemies .

input: I will to France hoping that the consequence will be bitter, black, and tragical.
target: A dire induction am I witness to , And will to France , hoping the consequence Will prove as bitter , black , and tragical .

input: Margaret, withdraw thee, wretched.
target: Withdraw thee , wretched Margaret .

input: Who arrives here?
target: Who comes here ?

input: My princes are poor!
target: Ah , my poor princes !

input: If your gentle souls fly in the air and be not fixed in doom, hover about me with your airy wings, and hear your mother's moan.
target: Ah , my tender babes , My unblown flowers , new-appearing sweets , If yet your gentle souls fly in the air And be not fixed in doom perpetual , Hover about me with your airy wings And hear your mother's lamentation .

input: Say that right for right Hath dimmed your infant's morn and aged night.
target: Hover about her ; say that right for right Hath dimmed your infant morn to aged night .

input: My voice has become crazy because my tongue is still and silent.
target: So many miseries have crazed my voice That my woe-wearied tongue is still and mute .

input: Why art, Edward Plantagenet, is dead.
target: Edward Plantagenet , why art thou dead ?

input: Is it possible to fly from such gentle lambs and then throw them in the wolves' entrails?
target: Wilt thou , O God , fly from such gentle lambs And throw them in the entrails of the wolf ?

input: When was the last time you slept when such a deed was done?
target: When didst thou sleep when such a deed was done ?

input: Let my griefs frown on the upper hand, because I want mine to benefit from seigniory.
